<HEAD>`Aging Rabble-Rouser' Address Capital's Elite at Son's Graduation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Mario </PERSON> <PERSON> Savio </PERSON> called himself `` not just an aging rabble-rouser but a parent also'' as the pioneer of the student movement of the 1960s spoke at his son's graduation from a prestigious <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> high school. The one-time <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> California </ORGANIZATION> at <LOCATION> Berkeley </LOCATION> firebrand who helped trigger the student power movement also described his change during college from being `` a most unpolitical son of unpolitical Italian immigrants.'' `` We came to view <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> as a racist and imperialist power ... -LRB- that -RRB- covered its tracks with a beguiling opportunity for self expression,'' the 45-year-old told the class at <ORGANIZATION> Sidwell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Friends </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION>. `` It was always right now in the'60s _ Freedom Now, <ORGANIZATION> Peace </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Now </ORGANIZATION>,'' he said. `` Did we not know that we could spoil the work by the way we dashed it off? We lived our lives as if we might not live to the ripe old age of 30. Even so ... we did not leave all our eggs in one basket. We bore children.'' <PERSON> Savio </PERSON>'s son, 18-year-old <PERSON> Nadav </PERSON> <PERSON> Savio </PERSON>, who plans to attend <ORGANIZATION> Wesleyan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Connecticut </LOCATION>, not <LOCATION> Berkeley </LOCATION>, told <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> for a story in Saturday's editions that he has not become involved in political issues. `` Some of what happened -LRB- in the 1960s -RRB- was excessive,'' he said. `` There was random and rampant drug experimentation. ... Some people went overboard in various ways, but there was a lot of good feeling among people and between people and that's something that should be resurrected.'' <PERSON> Savio </PERSON>, who dropped out of <LOCATION> Berkeley </LOCATION> in the mid-1960s, finally received his bachelor's degree in 1984 from <ORGANIZATION> San </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Francisco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>. He is now a graduate student and part-time lecturer in physics at <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> <LOCATION> State </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Nadav </PERSON> <PERSON> Savio </PERSON> lives in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> with his mother, <PERSON> Suzanne </PERSON> <PERSON> Goldberg </PERSON>, a psychologist who is married to Dr. <PERSON> Sidney </PERSON> <PERSON> Wolfe </PERSON>, director of the <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Citizen </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION>, a <PERSON> Ralph </PERSON> <PERSON> Nader </PERSON> organization. <PERSON> Savio </PERSON> is married for a second time and lives with his wife and their child in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION>.
