<HEAD>Contra Leader Calls for Renewed US Arms Aid</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A leader Nicaraguan resistance leader says Contra forces could face annihilation at the hands of the <ORGANIZATION> Sandinistas </ORGANIZATION> unless the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> resumes military aid to the rebels. The Contra leader, <PERSON> Adolfo </PERSON> <PERSON> Calero </PERSON>, said Friday at a news conference the aid was needed because of Sandinista threats to wipe out the insurgents if the latest round of peace talks did not produce a final settlement to the Nicaraguan war. Peace talks between the leftist Sandinista government and the Contras collapsed in <LOCATION> Managua </LOCATION> Thursday although both sides said a temporary truce would remain in effect. White House spokesman <PERSON> Marlin </PERSON> <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> was `` disappointed at the Sandinista rejection of the <ORGANIZATION> Nicaraguan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Resistance </ORGANIZATION> proposal to achieve democracy and an end to the war in <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>.'' The <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration blamed the Nicaraguan government for the breakdown in talks, but said no decision had been made about whether to ask <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> for more aid for the insurgents. `` I think that in view of the <ORGANIZATION> Sandinistas </ORGANIZATION>' actions here, their unwillingness to negotiate in good faith, their unwillingness to instill democratic reforms, you may well see a press for Contra aid from members of the Congress and from people in <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> and from other sources, but at this point we have made no decisions,'' said <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON>. Meanwhile, Rep. <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Kemp </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-N.Y. </LOCATION>, urged the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> to propose an aid package for the Contras that matches the amount of military assistance he said the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> provided to the Sandinista government during the first three months of this year. He put the amount at $ 105 million. <PERSON> Calero </PERSON>, indicated he felt that was a reasonable amount. The rebels have received no military aid since Feb. 29. The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> rejected President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s last military aid request for the Contras on Feb. 3. But Rep. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Bonior </PERSON>, D-Mich., a leader of the anti-Contra forces in the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> said, `` This is no time to be talking of military aid. He called for additional efforts to achieve a peace settlement before a new military aid request is considered. The goal of the latest negotiating round, which began on Tuesday, was to end the war and install democratic reforms, in accordance with a preliminary peace plan signed on March 23 in <LOCATION> Sapoa </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>. The discussions had been described as the fourth and final round of a series which have taken place under an interim truce.
