<HEAD>Jackson Focuses On Economics</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By F.N. D'ALESSIO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>, back in his home territory for the weekend, says he hopes to help forge an economic alliance among farmers and industrial workers. `` We want to bring people beyond racism, beyond sexism and beyond anti-Semitism,'' said <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>, in brief statements to reporters late Friday as he arrived in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> from a campaign swing in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> said he would unveil his new plans today in a speech at the headquarters of Operation Push, the civil rights group he founded. The candidate said his latest 40-day campaign plan would focus on economic proposals. `` We'll focus on ways to protect workers, farmers, the aged and the poor against the ravages of Reagonomics,'' he said. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> was asked about polls indicating he would hurt <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> Gov. <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> as a running mate against the Republican ticket headed by <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>. `` If we are within four points of <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> before the race begins, we have the capacity to win,'' <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> replied. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> came in second place to <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> in delegate and popular vote count in the Democratic primaries, but a survey published in <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> suggested he would hurt the ticket among groups whose support the <ORGANIZATION> Democrats </ORGANIZATION> need to win in the fall. And another poll, conducted for <ORGANIZATION> USA </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Today </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cable </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Network </ORGANIZATION>, indicated a Dukakis-led ticket with <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> as the running mate would lose to <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, 47 percent to 40 percent. Otherwise, <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> would win, 45 percent to 39 percent, the survey suggested. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> has said only that <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> deserves to be considered, not that he has any special claim on the job. Confusion over <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>'s position on the matter has been heightened in recent days by a <ORGANIZATION> Cable </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Network </ORGANIZATION> report that quoted him as saying he wants to be vice president. `` Let's leave it at consideration,'' <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> said Friday in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> when asked to clarify the matter. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> has said he deserves to be offered a spot on the ticket, but the <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News-Post </ORGANIZATION> survey found that two-thirds of <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> voters believe the nominee has the right to `` choose anyone he wants'' as a running mate. Only three in 10 said the second spot on the ticket should automatically go to the second-place finisher in the primaries, the poll said. The ABC-Post poll said <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> was the vice presidential choice of 36 percent of all registered Democrats. However, nearly one-quarter of those surveyed said they would be less likely to vote for <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> if <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> were on the ticket. Only 12 percent said they would be more likely to vote Democratic with <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> in the No. 2 spot, the poll said. Earlier Friday, <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> said in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> that he has better credentials than anyone else in politics to be the Democratic vice presidential nominee. While others may be qualified, <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> said, none has shown ability to win 7 million votes as he did in the primary season or has his combination of regional and political strengths to balance a ticket headed by <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>. `` We meet virtually every stated qualification for serious consideration on the ticket,'' he said. `` No one else at this point that's active in politics has shown the breadth of support I have shown at the voting polls; no one else has shown the ability to impact on the country's tone and the party's priorities. `` They may have state credentials. They've not shown themselves to have national vote-getting potential,'' <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> told reporters who accompanied him to a two-day working vacation at the posh La Costa health spa north of <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Diego </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> left La Costa Friday afternoon to head to return to <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>, where he planned to meet with civil rights leaders and continue plans for the convention. Although visibly tired and talking very softly after his long flight, <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> brought a touch of <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> casualness to the chilly <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> night. The often soberly dressed candidate was wearing blue jeans, leather sandals and a black jacket bearing the emblem of the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Longshoremen </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Warehousemen </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION>. He also wore a silver pin in the form of a stevedore's pick _ a symbol of the union.
