<DATELINE>OSLO, Norway (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Norway </LOCATION> have agreed that Norwegian experts can inspect a shipment of Norwegian heavy water, a chemical used in the production of nuclear weapons. Foreign Trade Minister <PERSON> Kurt </PERSON> <PERSON> Mosbakk </PERSON> told <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> on Friday that an agreement on the inspection was negotiated by <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Norway </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Oslo </LOCATION> earlier this week, the national news agency <ORGANIZATION> NTB </ORGANIZATION> reported. The news agency said <PERSON> Mosbakk </PERSON> told parliament that about half of the 20 tons of heavy water sold to <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> in 1959 had vanished through waste and evaporation. Norwegian experts would be allowed to inspect the remaining half, <ORGANIZATION> NTB </ORGANIZATION> said. When <LOCATION> Norway </LOCATION> sold <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> the water almost 30 years ago the contract stipulated that <LOCATION> Norway </LOCATION> had the right to inspect the water and that it could be used for peaceful purposes only. <LOCATION> Norway </LOCATION> did not raise the question of inspection until <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> nuclear technician <PERSON> Mordechai </PERSON> <PERSON> Vanunu </PERSON> told a British newspaper that <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> had used heavy water to produce plutonium for use in nuclear weapons. <PERSON> Vanunu </PERSON> is serving an 18-year prison term in <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> for treason. In three previous rounds of negotiations about the inspection issue, <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> rejected a <LOCATION> Norwegian </LOCATION> proposal to transfer its inspection right to the Vienna-based <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Atom </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION>. Since <LOCATION> Norway </LOCATION> started production of heavy water in the late 1930s, about 450 tons have been exported, mostly for scientific research. Ten countries, including <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>, received amounts large enough for use in nuclear reactors. Two nuclear powers, <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, received heavy water from <LOCATION> Norway </LOCATION> on the condition that they did no re-export it. Seven other import countries have signed the nuclear non-proliferation treaty, which allows on-site inspection. <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> has not signed the treaty.
