<HEAD>UNESCO Plays Down Controversial Communications Order</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HARRY DUNPHY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> UNESCO </ORGANIZATION> officials have backed away from a proposal to create a global communications order that some Western nations viewed as a threat to the freedom of the press. The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> observer to <ORGANIZATION> UNESCO </ORGANIZATION> cautiously praised the recommendations, released by the group's executive board Friday. The new communications strategy played down establishing a new world information and communication order. The concept lay at the heart of a decade-old debate at the 158-nation <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Educational </ORGANIZATION>, Scientific and Cultural Organization and helped convince the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> to withdraw. The board's recommendations go to <ORGANIZATION> UNESCO </ORGANIZATION> Director General <PERSON> Federico </PERSON> <PERSON> Mayor </PERSON>, who is trying to persuade those two nations to rejoin. The report's communications section admitted that journalists had widely interpreted <ORGANIZATION> UNESCO </ORGANIZATION>'s efforts to establish a new world order as aimed at `` undermining freedom of information.'' `` This resulted in a misunderstanding that was used to sully the organization's image,'' it said. The section said <ORGANIZATION> UNESCO </ORGANIZATION> should `` explore the possibilities of a new strategy ... that will dispel the misunderstanding.'' It said the strategy should emphasize `` development of critical acumen among -LRB- media -RRB- users, the ability for individuals and communities to react to any kind of manipulation -LRB- by the media -RRB- and to become familiair with the means available to users to defend their right of reply.'' The section also said <ORGANIZATION> UNESCO </ORGANIZATION> should seek to `` ensure a free and wider and more balanced flow of information.'' In the past, Western governments and media groups have tried to replace the words `` more balanced'' with `` unrestricted.'' These governments and Western media groups expressed concern that the proposed new world communications order could lead to codes of conduct and licensing of journalists. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> observer <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> T. </PERSON> <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> said the latest recommendations, approved by consensus without a vote, contained `` scope for positive change.'' `` However, I am distressed at the tone'' in the communications section, which `` tries to set up an adversary relationship between the media and its audience.'' The board's recommendations, presented at the end of its spring meeting, are intended to guide Mayor in preparation of <ORGANIZATION> UNESCO </ORGANIZATION>'s plan of activities for the l990s At the board's opening meeting three weeks ago, Mayor, a <LOCATION> Spanish </LOCATION> scientist who took office in November, proposed that <ORGANIZATION> UNESCO </ORGANIZATION>'s 14 major programs be reduced to five. He suggested that the organization should do fewer things but do them better and with more follow-up. The board has recommended cutting programs to seven. It added one dealing with peace, human rights and elimination of discrimination, and another that covers development studies. A group of 77 Third World countries and the Soviet bloc criticized Mayor for dropping these programs from his plan for the 1990s. Along with communications, the peace and human rights proposals have provoked controversial debates in the past. Mayor will use the document prepared by the board to draft an outline of the plan for the 1990s for the fall meeting of the board.
