<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION>'s increasingly open press has reported that federal authorities were worried about a popular uprising if they seized control in <LOCATION> Slovenia </LOCATION>, the nation's most liberal republic. The ruling <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, meanwhile, called for radical economic changes on Friday, including freer, profit-oriented markets and more foreign investment to overcome <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION>'s deepening economic crisis Reports have circulated for several weeks that military authorities in <LOCATION> Slovenia </LOCATION> were thinking about stepping in to quell liberal tendencies in the northernmost of <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION>'s six republics. Federal officials and Communist leaders in the republic have denied any plans for such an action. But <ORGANIZATION> NIN </ORGANIZATION> magazine on Friday published what it said were excerpts of a transcript of a discussion of the police role after such a takeover. A police official, whom the magazine did not identify, was quoted as speaking of police ability `` to control the situation after the arrests, since it is believed that the people will come out into the streets.'' NIN also quoted <PERSON> Igor </PERSON> <PERSON> Bavcar </PERSON>, a spokesman for a group formed to fight the arrests of two journalists who first wrote of the alleged takeover, as saying the transcript means `` nobody believes that the stories about the coup have been fabricated.'' Authorities have denied any link between the journalists report on the takeover and their arrests last week by military authorities. Police have said the journalists were arrested along with a soldier after an unmarked document on combat readiness was found in their possession. <PERSON> Bavcar </PERSON> said his group would decide this weekend whether or not to call for a 15-minute general strike next Tuesday in protest at the arrests. The Slovenian daily Delo reported from <LOCATION> Ljubljana </LOCATION> that more than 7,000 people have signed a petition calling for the release of the trio. Money is pouring into a special account to help the families of those held, and more than 200 companies, Communist party cells and trade union groups have backed the petition for release, <PERSON> Delo </PERSON> said. <LOCATION> Slovenia </LOCATION>'s official lawyers' union issued a statement saying public unease over the case should be seen as popular concern over preserving gains of democratization. `` State organs can not any longer demand in advance uncritical trust from the people,'' the lawyers said, calling for strict adherence to the law in the handling of the controversial case. The party's 52-page blueprint for economic change, largely adopted at a party conference last month, advocated `` the strengthening of market mechanisms'' and recomended measures to attract `` the investment of more foreign capital'' in the Yugoslav economy. It said the party supported `` investment of private funds'' in small businesses as a means of `` restructuring the economy and overcoming high unemployment.'' `` The theses call for sweeping economic reforms to ensure the autonomy of enterprises, the full affirmation of all elements of the market and of economic laws, a single home market and an opening to the world,'' the document said. <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION> suffers from 150 percent inflation, a $ 21 billion debt, worker unrest and heavily endebted firms. The government recently undertook a strict austerity program curbing wages and spending as part of sweeping changes to be completed before the end of the year. One of the party's most radical proposals is to base the economy, for the first time, on the profit motive, ending the practice of subsidizing and, when necessary, rescuing money-losing enterprises. The party blueprint also contained a reference to human rights, widely seen as a victory for a liberal faction in the party.
