<HEAD>Commencement Brings Vindication for Tardy Scholar</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES LITKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A man whose doctoral dissertation was rejected by a faculty committee in 1942 but hailed by historians four decades later as a pioneering work has received his Ph.D. `` Celebrity is a new status and it's hard to get used to,'' <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Bourgin </PERSON>, who gained national attention earlier this year when his dissertation was finally accepted, said Friday. `` But if all this hoopla was n't going on, I think I'd be feeling quite depressed,'' said the 77-year-old retired civil servant, who lives in <LOCATION> Chevy </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Chase </LOCATION>, Md. `` My polio is acting up, my walking ability is reduced and I'm having difficulty getting out of a chair. `` But this attention, the commencement,'' he added, `` is such great compensation.'' <PERSON> Bourgin </PERSON> was a graduate student at <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> and a disciple of the late Professor <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Merriam </PERSON>, the leading political scientist of the day and a member of then-President <PERSON> Franklin </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Roosevelt </PERSON>'s circle of advisers known as the `` Brain Trust. Under <PERSON> Merriam </PERSON>'s guidance, <PERSON> Bourgin </PERSON> re-examined the history of government planning in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. He then argued in his dissertation that the country's early leaders, <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON> <PERSON> Hamilton </PERSON> and <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Jefferson </PERSON> among them, had intended to use the powers of the federal government to develop the fledgling nation's resources through public works and other projects. The paper challenged the then-common conviction that <ORGANIZATION> Roosevelt </ORGANIZATION>'s New Deal social programs marked a departure from laissez-faire principles attributed to the founding fathers By the time his paper was rejected as not yet `` in satisfactory shape,'' <PERSON> Bourgin </PERSON> was married with a child to support. He said he could n't afford to return to campus as a full-time student to revise his manuscript, so he locked it away in a box. In the intervening years, he manufactured light fixtures, owned a chain of men's clothing stores in <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION> and became a federal civil servant, eventually rising to become regional director for the <ORGANIZATION> federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Emergency </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Planning </ORGANIZATION>, supervising a five-state region in the <LOCATION> Midwest </LOCATION>. `` But I never changed my mind on the essential idea I'd developed in my paper,'' he recalled `` I maintained my interest in history, I looked everywhere, and whenever I read, I was constantly looking to see if someone else had it. `` I was so convinced I was right, and so convinced of the importance of it that tenacity was the easy part,'' he said. <PERSON> Bourgin </PERSON>'s reward came last year, when he read historian <PERSON> Arthur </PERSON> <PERSON> Schlesinger </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>'s `` Cycles of American History,'' a chapter of which made essentially the same argument <PERSON> Bourgin </PERSON>'s paper had offered nearly a half-century earlier. He wrote to <PERSON> Schlesinger </PERSON>, who looked at the dissertation and wrote back: `` Congratulations on your path-breaking work ... I am astonished by the fate of your thesis at <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>.'' Emboldened, <PERSON> Bourgin </PERSON> set in process a motion that culminated Friday with <PERSON> Bourgin </PERSON> receiving his doctorate. `` I'm not sure how the paper was rejected the first time, but my best guess is that after professor <PERSON> Merriam </PERSON> retired, my dissertation became a kind of orphan. `` Also, I was already working at making a living while it was being considered and I think the chairman of the department at the time may not have wanted the degree cheapened by giving it to someone who would n't use it,'' <PERSON> Bourgin </PERSON> said. `` I do n't know if all that makes it any sweeter,'' he said. `` But it certainly has made the last few months of my life an interesting time.''
