 Union leaders criticized the <LOCATION> Suffolk </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> executive for his veto of a bill that would have made the county the nation's first major municipality to regulate video display terminals. `` I'm outraged at the county executive's submissiveness to the business community, whose arguments of the cost of the legislation are innocuous and untrue,'' state <ORGANIZATION> AFL-CIO </ORGANIZATION> President <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Cleary </PERSON> saud Friday. But Executive <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> <PERSON> Halpin </PERSON> told reporters that several businesses threatened to leave the county or cancel relocation plans if he signed the legislation. `` In both cases, the consequence would be hundreds, if not thousands of jobs lost, and these are losses that I do not think <LOCATION> Suffolk </LOCATION> can afford,'' <PERSON> Halpin </PERSON> said. Under the bill, employers would be required to pay 80 percent of the cost of eye examinations, glass lenses and frames on a yearly basis, if needed. It also required 15-minute work breaks every three hours and outlined strict work station standards, including what type of chairs should be used, adjustability of the terminals and office lighting. `` This law would cost local businesses millions of dollars to implement at the same time that their competitors in other areas faced no restrictions,'' <PERSON> Halpin </PERSON> said. `` This would be an economic disadvantage to them of no small consequence.'' <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> Rechler </PERSON>, chairman of the Association for a <ORGANIZATION> Better </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Long </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Island </ORGANIZATION>, a group of 40 developers, said after the veto was announced Friday: `` The economy of <LOCATION> Suffolk </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> has just breathed a sigh of relief.'' The Legislature could override <PERSON> Halpin </PERSON>'s veto with 12 votes. The measure was originally approved by 13 of the 18 legislators.
