<HEAD>Kitchen Band Entertains Nursing Home Residents With Old Songs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>McHENRY, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A band of widows low on talent but high on spirit grabbed a few unconventional musical instruments _ a washboard, a soap bottle filled with beans and a teapot _ donned floral aprons, and embarked on a sentimental journey. `` You do n't have to have talent,'' said one of the Happy Tooters, <PERSON> Frances </PERSON> <PERSON> Widhalm </PERSON>, after a recent performance. `` Almost none of us does. All you have to do is like music.'' At 88, Mrs. <PERSON> Widhalm </PERSON> is the oldest of the Happy Tooters, with the youngest being 62. The 15 women, all widows, perform at nursing homes and retirement villages, choosing their material with people their own age in mind. The songs are traditional, like `` Melody of Love,'' `` Alley Cat'' and `` Peg O' My Heart.'' The orchestration, however, is anything but traditional. The Happy Tooters play kazoos, shake soap bottles filled with beans and croon into the spouts of teapots. Pianist <PERSON> Isabelle </PERSON> <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> and drummer <PERSON> Madeline </PERSON> <PERSON> Behm </PERSON> play the only `` real'' instruments, but someone occasionally chimes in on the triangle. Like any band worth its gigs, the Happy Tooters have uniforms _ blue floral aprons over white blouses with blue floral bonnets to match. `` I've never sat in the audience, so I do n't know what we sound like,'' said <PERSON> Marion </PERSON> <PERSON> Schmitt </PERSON>, 74, of <PERSON> McHenry </PERSON>. `` But we do have fun, and I think we do bring pleasure to people.'' Mrs. <PERSON> Schmitt </PERSON>, the band's organizer and conductor, said she first organized a kitchen band in November 1985, when her chapter of <PERSON> Naim </PERSON>, a Roman Catholic support group for widows and widowers, was slated to provide entertainment at a dinner in the <LOCATION> Rockford </LOCATION> diocese. The Happy Tooters made their debut March 9, 1986. It was supposed to be a one-shot deal, but the show biz bug bit. They've been touring northern <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> ever since _ weather permitting `` The ladies are getting up in age,'' Mrs. <PERSON> Schmitt </PERSON> explained. `` We try not to peform too much in July and August, when it's hot.'' Cold weather and rain can also be a problem. `` We do n't like to travel when the weather is unstable, we're such a bunch of crips,'' Mrs. <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> said `` But playing for people makes us feel better.'' Mrs. <PERSON> Schmitt </PERSON> pointed out to the elderly and infirm people who were beginning to gather in the activity room at a home before a performance. `` You see some pretty sad faces out there,'' she said. `` It makes us feel good to see them smile.''
