<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A federal jury will take the weekend off before resuming deliberations in a cigarette liability lawsuit carried on by the widower of a lung-cancer victim who smoked for 40 years. The jury considering the <PERSON> Cipollone </PERSON> case ended their fourth day of deliberations about 5 p.m. Friday with no verdict. It will resume deliberations Monday. Jurors asked few questions during deliberations, which began at noon Tuesday. They are considering whether or not to award damages to <PERSON> Antonio </PERSON> <PERSON> Cipollone </PERSON> for the 1984 death of his wife, <PERSON> Rose </PERSON>, at 58. During the four-month trial, he charged that cigarette-makers <ORGANIZATION> Lorillard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Liggett </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Philip </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Morris </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> misled the public about the dangers of cigarette smoking and contributed to Mrs. <PERSON> Cipollone </PERSON>'s death. The companies contend she made an intelligent, strong-willed choice to smoke knowing the risks. They argue smoking is not a proven cancer-cause, and that her type of cancer is n't linked to cigarettes anyway. On Friday, jurors asked if the 1984 Surgeon General's report on smoking and health was in evidence and whether they could see it. It was n't, and the judge said they could n't.
