<FIRST>r a PM-SoCalQuake     06-11 0460</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-SoCal Quake,0473</SECOND>
<HEAD>Quake Jolts Southern, Central California, Shuts Down Major
Aqueduct</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE SIEGEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Southern and central Californians were jolted by a strong earthquake that sent rocks flying onto a freeway and closed an aqueduct that supplies half of <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>' water. Three people in nearby <LOCATION> Whittier </LOCATION> were injured by a falling avocado tree in Friday's earthquake. One woman was treated at the scene and two men were taken to a hospital for tests. The quake forced the closure of the 440-mile-long <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> Aqueduct when power to at least two pumping plants was knocked out. The temblor, measuring 5.2 on the <PERSON> Richter </PERSON> scale, struck at 4:06 p.m. and was centered on the <LOCATION> Garlock </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Fault </LOCATION>, 11 miles north-northeast of <LOCATION> Gorman </LOCATION>, or about 70 miles northwest of downtown <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>, said <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Finn </PERSON>, a spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> California </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Technology </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Pasadena </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Water </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Resources </ORGANIZATION> officials in <LOCATION> Sacramento </LOCATION> said crews worked overnight to reopen the aqueduct and that the city should not face a water shortage. `` For <LOCATION> L.A. </LOCATION> there's no problem, the storage lakes have an ample water supply,'' said <PERSON> Mike </PERSON> <PERSON> McGregor </PERSON>, a spokesman for the state <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Water </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Resources </ORGANIZATION>. He said the aqueduct would remain closed at least through today. But he said the <LOCATION> Antelope </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley-East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Water </LOCATION> <LOCATION> District </LOCATION>, about 50 miles north of downtown <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>, was asked to conserve because it had a smaller supply. The quake catapulted rocks onto the northbound lanes of Interstate 5 near the Grapevine, but traffic continued to flow while crews removed the rocks, said <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> Highway Patrol Officer <PERSON> Jerry </PERSON> <PERSON> Berger </PERSON> at the <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Tejon </LOCATION> station. There were no immediate reports of accidents from the rockslide, he said. `` It was a real violent jolt,'' <PERSON> Berger </PERSON> said. A series of aftershocks also were measured by <ORGANIZATION> Caltech </ORGANIZATION>, with the biggest measuring 4.0 on the <PERSON> Richter </PERSON> scale at 4:22 p.m., said <PERSON> Riley </PERSON> <PERSON> Geary </PERSON>, a seismic analyst. The Garlock Fault, where the quake struck, is the second-largest fault in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, with a length of 200 miles, compared with the 600-mile-long <ORGANIZATION> San </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Andreas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fault </ORGANIZATION>, said <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Geological Survey seismologist <PERSON> Lucile </PERSON> <PERSON> Jones </PERSON>. The Richter scale measures ground motion as recorded on seismographs. Every increase of one number means a tenfold increase in magnitude. Thus a reading of 7.5 reflects an earthquake 10 times stronger than one of 6.5. An earthquake of 3.5 on the <PERSON> Richter </PERSON> scale can cause slight damage in the local area, 4 moderate damage, 5 considerable damage, 6 severe damage. A 7 reading is a `` major'' earthquake, capable of widespread heavy damage; 8 is a `` great'' quake, capable of tremendous damage. The <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> earthquake of 1906, which occurred before the <PERSON> Richter </PERSON> scale was devised, has been estimated at 8.3 on the <PERSON> Richter </PERSON> scale.
