<HEAD>Army To Speed Up Appeal Process For Detainees</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 15 grafs to UPDATE with comments from Palestinian
lawyer on appeals process. PICKS up 16th graf, `Israel radio .. .'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By KARIN LAUB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The army ordered a speedup in the judicial review process for some of the 5,000 Palestinian arrested during the Arab uprising in the occupied territories. Defense officials said the new system would benefit detainees by increasing judicial supervision. But Palestinian lawyer <PERSON> Jonathan </PERSON> <PERSON> Kuttab </PERSON> today called the move a charade and said <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> Minister <PERSON> Yitzhak </PERSON> <PERSON> Rabin </PERSON> ordered the changes after all detainees decided last week to challenge the system by filing appeals. About 2,000 Arabs are being held for up to six months without charges, most of them taken into custody since the uprising began Dec. 8. They are called administrative detainees. The army also holds about 3,000 Arabs awaiting trial or serving prison terms on charges of anti-Israeli violence. Underground leaders of the uprising set aside today as a `` Day of Solidarity'' with Palestinian prisoners and called for renewed anti-Israeli protests. On Friday, soldiers bulldozed the cinderblock house of an Arab from the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> refugee camp <PERSON> Jelazoun </PERSON> after he was arrested on suspicion that he stabbed an Israeli-appointed Arab mayor. In the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> village of <LOCATION> Beita </LOCATION>, troops expelled about 100 Israelis who were planting olive trees to protest the army's uprooting of orchards and demolition of 14 Arab houses The army measures were in reprisal for an April 6 clash between villagers and <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> teen-age <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> settlers in which two Arabs and a 15-year-old Jewish girl were killed. Also Friday, the Government Press Office reinstated the press credentials of <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Television </ORGANIZATION> correspondend <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> Fletcher </PERSON> after a six-week