<HEAD>Radicals Stage Firebomb Attack On Government Building</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 9 grafs to UPDATE with more details on attack on
government buildings, clashes in two other cities. Pickup 10th
graf, ``Our struggle...''
^By C.W. LIM</NOTE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Radical students hurling firebombs attacked the <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> and the prime minister's office today, and student leaders vowed to stage another march to <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> for unification talks. Police said 26 students forced their way past guards at a back gate of the Combined Central Government Building in downtown <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION> and hurled at least 10 firebombs at the complex. Eight of the attackers barricaded themselves in a third-floor cafeteria before they were seized by police. Nobody was injured in the attack in which windows were smashed and a police guard post and a waiting room blackened by flames and smoke. Police said they arrested 18 attackers and that the others fled. The building, across the street from the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION>, houses the prime minister's office, the <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> and other major government departments. Small clashes also were reported today in the provincial cities of <LOCATION> Taeju </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Kwangju </LOCATION> as riot police firing volleys of tear gas dispersed students hurling rocks and firebombs. No injuries or arrests were immediately reported. The attacks were mounted after riot police blocked thousands of radical students on Friday from mounting a march to the North Korean border for talks on reuniting the divided <LOCATION> Korean </LOCATION> peninsula. Fighting began on Friday when police fired tear gas to drive back students who hurled firebombs and battled with rocks and clubs to try and break through to the border. Police officials said today that more than 800 students were arrested in the clashes the day before. More than 100 police and students were injured in the street clashes, they said. About 60,000 riot police were deployed to halt the march to the border truce site of <LOCATION> Panmunjom </LOCATION>. Riot police remained on alert today and troopers guarded key government buildings and <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> diplomatic offices. Radical leaders at a rally today at <ORGANIZATION> Yonsei </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> in the west of <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION> vowed to mount another march to the border on Aug. 15, national independence day, and said they would not abandon the reunification drive. `` Our struggle has ignited the mind of the people who want reunficition of our land,'' one leader said in a speech. About 2,000 students applauded the speakers and shouted slogans. But the students' mood was subdued and thousands of others who had gathered at the campus for the march Friday left overnight. Speakers continued to denounce the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and demand the withdrawal of the 42,000 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> troops based in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> under a mutual defense pact. `` Yankee go home'' and `` Reunification,'' students chanted. Radicals claim the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> enforces partition of the <LOCATION> Korean </LOCATION> <LOCATION> peninsula </LOCATION> so it can rule the south as a virtual colony. A wave of violent anti-American protests has hit <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> during the past month. The radicals, who represent between 10 percent and 20 percent of college students, have failed to attract popular support with their reunification campaign. The main opposition parties urged radicals to abandon the march, saying it lacked public support. Most people in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> fear the totalitarian north is determined to conquer the south. <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> invaded the south in 1950 to start the Korean War and the two nations remain bitter opponents. The North Korean government said its student delegates waited Friday at <LOCATION> Panmunjom </LOCATION> for the South Korean students. It denounced the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korean </LOCATION> government, claiming they want to block reunification.
