<HEAD>Pro-Government Paper Joins Outcry Over New Press Curbs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID CRARY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A loyal pro-government newspaper today joined the outcry against new press restrictions, and a prominent black moderate pleaded for the release of jailed guerrilla leader <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON> <PERSON> Mandela </PERSON>. The new restrictions took effect Friday when the government reimposed the nationwide state of emergency for a third year. They tighten curbs on reporting about opposition activity and require some journalists to register with the government. The Citizen, a pro-government <LOCATION> Johannesburg </LOCATION> daily, joined a wide range of journalists, anti-apartheid leaders and others in criticizing the restrictions. `` There is only one word for the new press curbs and that is overkill,'' The Citizen's editorial said. It said the government appeared to have reached the point where it was barring newspapers from reporting `` matters of vital concern to everyone.'' It added: `` That will mean the public will be uninformed and subject to rumor.' The <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Correspondents </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> said in a statement: `` We observe with irony that <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> is progressively shutting down the free flow of information at a time when the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> _ frequently depicted here as an enemy of press freedom _ is noticeably moving towards a more open society.'' <PERSON> Mangosuthu </PERSON> <PERSON> Buthelezi </PERSON>, leader of the <ORGANIZATION> KwaZulu </ORGANIZATION> homeland and one of the blacks the government would like to draw into a white-controlled power-sharing arrangement, said the extension of the emergency was a tragedy. At an outdoor meeting near <LOCATION> Durban </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Buthelezi </PERSON> also appealed for the release of <PERSON> Mandela </PERSON>, who is serving a life prison sentence for his actions as leader of the outlawed <ORGANIZATION> African </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> guerrilla movement. `` Black <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> will not rest until he is free,'' <PERSON> Buthelezi </PERSON> said. `` Nothing the South African government can do will gain it credibility while it treats Dr. <PERSON> Mandela </PERSON> as a dangerous enemy.'' <PERSON> Buthelezi </PERSON> said <PERSON> Mandela </PERSON> might be the only person capable of ending a bloody power stuggle in <LOCATION> Natal </LOCATION> province between militants who support the <ORGANIZATION> ANC </ORGANIZATION> and more conservative blacks who follow <PERSON> Buthelezi </PERSON>. `` I believe he -LRB- <PERSON> Mandela </PERSON> -RRB- would come out of jail to thump anybody ... who set black brother against black brother on the eve of a final black victory over apartheid,'' <PERSON> Buthelezi </PERSON> said. As he spoke, about 70,000 fans packed <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Wembley </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Stadium </LOCATION> for a 10-hour rock concert honoring <PERSON> Mandela </PERSON>. Although the <ORGANIZATION> British </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Broadcasting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> pledged to cover the extravaganza as a musical, not a political event, its commentator referred to <PERSON> Mandela </PERSON> as `` a political prisoner.'' The South African government threatened this week to expel the <ORGANIZATION> BBC </ORGANIZATION> for its allegedly biased coverage of the government. One of the new restrictions imposed in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> on Friday outlaws advocacy of a boycott of nationwide municipal elections scheduled for October. Most major anti-apartheid groups, including 17 which were banned in February, oppose black participation in elections organized by the white authorities until blacks have voting rights on a national level. The new regulations make it illegal to quote anti-government statements from members of the 17 organizations and prohibit newspapers from quoting any <ORGANIZATION> ANC </ORGANIZATION> members. Another new rule requires local news agencies, except for the <ORGANIZATION> South </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> African </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, to register with the government. These small domestic news agencies, many of them aggressive in covering anti-apartheid activity, could be ordered to submit their dispatches to a government censor. A group of these alternative news agencies _ the <ORGANIZATION> East </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cape </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agencies </ORGANIZATION> _ said the new regulation could be `` the first step on the road to compulsory registration of all journalists ... with the threat of deregistration if they misbehave. The government `` seeks a nation of ignorant, pliant subjects,'' it said.
