<HEAD>Prison Population Falls Below Court-Ordered Cap</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE LINDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The city's jail population dropped below the court-ordered limit, allowing the city to hold prisoners unable to raise bail, officials said. The jail population this morning was 3,813, under the 3,850 maximum permitted by the court on weekends and holidays, Bail Commissioner <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Murray </PERSON> said. For other days, the maximum prison population is set at 3,750. Since Wednesday many people, including alleged drug dealers, had avoided jail when unable to raise bail because of the order by <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Norma </PERSON> <PERSON> Shapiro </PERSON> that limited the city's prison population. At the time the jails held nearly 4,000 men and women. The city began freeing prisoners on their own recognizance if they were awaiting trial and had been unable to raise bail of $ 2,500 or less. On Friday afternoon, Prison Superintendent <PERSON> Edmund </PERSON> <PERSON> Lyons </PERSON> said the jails held 3,690 people and that, starting this morning, those unable to raise bail would be held. `` The prison is open and people can be admitted on a regular basis,'' <PERSON> Murray </PERSON> said early today. `` The moratorium right now is lifted.'' District Attorney <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> Castille </PERSON> has termed the jail moratorium `` lunacy,'' charging that city prisons can hold as many as 4,300 inmates. <PERSON> Castille </PERSON> called on Mayor <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON> <PERSON> Goode </PERSON> to seek to have the cap raised or find alternate confinement space. Prisoners who brought the lawsuit charged that <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION>'s prisons were overcrowded They had demanded that each of the city's 3,200 cells should have only one person Excluded from the moratorium are those charged with murder, attempted murder, rape, attempted rape, kidnapping, arson, robbery and aggravated assault in addition to crimes involving use of a gun or knife or large amounts of drugs. Meanwhile, the city moved closer to increasing its cell space by awarding a construction contract for a new $ 165 million Criminal Justice Center. The center _ with jail space for 440 people, plus courtrooms _ is expected to be completed in 1991.
