<HEAD>Saragat, Former Italian President, Dead At 89</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Former President <PERSON> Giuseppe </PERSON> <PERSON> Saragat </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>'s first socialist president and a strong supporter of workers' rights, died today of complications from heart disease, an official said. He was 89. <PERSON> Saragat </PERSON>, a founder of the <ORGANIZATION> Social </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democrat </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, died at his house in <LOCATION> Rome </LOCATION>, said a party official who spoke on condition of anonymity. The former president had suffered from cardiovascular problems for years. <PERSON> Saragat </PERSON> became the fifth president of the <LOCATION> Italian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Republic </LOCATION> in 1964. After he left office in 1971, he served as president of his party. In 1922, at the age of 24, <PERSON> Saragat </PERSON> joined the <ORGANIZATION> Socialist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> but left <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION> after Fascist dictator <PERSON> Benito </PERSON> <PERSON> Mussolini </PERSON> came to power the same year. <PERSON> Saragat </PERSON> fled to <LOCATION> Austria </LOCATION> and then in 1926 to <PERSON> Saint-Gaudens </PERSON>, <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>. He returned to <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION> after the Italian armistice with the Allies in 1943 and was arrested for anti-Fascist activity. He escaped, was recaptured and escaped a second time together with <PERSON> Sandro </PERSON> <PERSON> Petrini </PERSON>, who also later became president. In 1946, <PERSON> Saragat </PERSON> became president of the <ORGANIZATION> Constituent </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION> that framed <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>'s republican postwar constitution. He broke with the Socialists in 1947 and helped found the <ORGANIZATION> Socialist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Italian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION>, whic