<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 In a victory for anti-abortion groups, Presbyterian leaders have urged a change in the denomination's pro-choice position, while others struggled with a major church statement on nuclear weapons A subcommittee today continued revising `` Christian Obedience in a Nuclear Age,'' a paper that has been criticized by groups within the Presbyterian Church -LRB- <LOCATION> U.S.A. </LOCATION> -RRB- who say it improperly glorifies civil disobedience and resistance to government policies. Abortion and nuclear weapons were among the controversial issues being debated during the nine-day meeting of the 3-million-member church's 200th <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION>, which ends Wednesday. On Friday, full committees of the assembly adopted a wide-ranging statement on religious freedom, including recommendations that pastors give up their tax exemptions for their housing allowances, and adopted a paper titled `` Is Christ Divided?'' which complains that special interest groups have split the denomination and calls for more serious theological discussion of issues. A committee Friday called for a change in the church's position on abortion and a new study of the issue, but supporters of the denomination's generally pro-choice position say they expect a floor fight on the question. The assembly is scheduled to consider the matter on Tuesday. Presbyterians Pro-Life, a sanctioned organization within the denomination, wants the church to condemn abortion in all instances except where the mother's life is in danger. <ORGANIZATION> PPL </ORGANIZATION> co-sponsored an appearance by Nobel Peace laureate <PERSON> Mother </PERSON> <PERSON> Teresa </PERSON> in a rally before the convention began Tuesday. <ORGANIZATION> PPL </ORGANIZATION> hoped <PERSON> Mother </PERSON> <PERSON> Teresa </PERSON>'s reputation and staunch anti-abortion stance would persuade commissioners to approve a new study, or a change in church policy. Currently, the Presbyterian group opposes abortion as a method of birth control, but says the decision rests with a woman in consultation with her doctor and her conscience. Also Friday, the 18-member <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Obedience </ORGANIZATION> subcommittee retained language in the <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Obedience </ORGANIZATION> paper that calls nuclear war immoral, but changed a section labeling the theory of nuclear deterrence immoral. T. LaFontine `` Fountain'' <PERSON> Odom </PERSON>, an elder from <LOCATION> Charlotte </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.C. </LOCATION>, said the subcommittee revised the paper to say `` nuclear deterrence as an end in itself'' is immoral. In addition, the subcommittee deleted recommendations calling on local church groups to provide financial and moral support to those who resist the government through tax protest and civil disobedience. But the subcommittee left in recommendations calling for creation of a voluntary Fund for Obedience to a High Authority `` for the assistance of those who suffer financial loss or difficulty as a result of acts of conscience.'' Many conservatives have blamed the <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Obedience </ORGANIZATION> paper and past social policy statements for the denomination's membership decline. There were 2,976,937 church members in 1987, a decline of 154,191 since 1983, when the denomination was formed from two Presbyterian groups that had split during the Civil War. The denomination is almost 14 times larger than the second-largest group, the <ORGANIZATION> Presbyterian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>.
