<BYLINE>By JUDY FARAH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WEST HOLLYWOOD, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A Teamsters union official says mandatory drug testing of interstate truck and bus drivers is unreasonable and resembles a politically motivated `` witch hunt'' by federal highway safety officials. The <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Brotherhood </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Teamsters </ORGANIZATION> `` will fight this all the way,'' said R.V. <LOCATION> Durham </LOCATION>, the union's safety and health director. The Teamsters represent 200,000 truckers nationwide. <LOCATION> Durham </LOCATION> responded Friday to a highway safety proposal by Secretary of <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Jim </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Burnley </ORGANIZATION> for drug testing of up to 5 million drivers of interstate trucks, passenger buses and vehicles hauling hazardous materials. `` We must act to identify those commercial drivers who abuse drugs and get them off the roads,'' <ORGANIZATION> Burnley </ORGANIZATION> told a news conference here. `` When one drugged truck or bus driver goes out on the road, he not only puts the lives of many people in danger, he gives the entire work force a bad reputation.'' But <PERSON> Durham </PERSON> said Teamster drivers are the safest and most responsible in the trucking industry and called the <ORGANIZATION> DOT </ORGANIZATION> proposal a `` witch hunt'' and `` a politically motivated move to beat up on truck drivers.'' <PERSON> Durham </PERSON> said that Teamster truckers were already subject to drug testing as part of their biannual transportation department physical exams, and also if there was probable suspicion of substance abuse. `` Random testing is an unreasonable and unjustifiable violation of a person's right to privacy. We believe government-mandated random testing is unconstitutional,'' <ORGANIZATION> Durham </ORGANIZATION> said. <ORGANIZATION> Burnley </ORGANIZATION>'s proposal was the latest in a series of department efforts to make <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s transportation network safer. In March, the drug testing program was proposed for the aviation industry. In May, the railroad industry was targeted. There are no firm statistics to indicate how many of the nation's truck drivers are drug abusers, he said. But he cited a June 1987 test of 317 tractor-trailer drivers in <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION> that showed 15 percent of the drivers tested positive for marijuana, cocaine and prescription stimulants. The proposed rule would cover 3 million to 5 million people who drive commercial motor vehicles weighing more than 10,000 pounds, vehicles that transport 16 or more people or vehicles that transport hazardous materials. School bus drivers and intercity bus drivers would not be affected by the proposal, he said. In <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trucking </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> endorsed the effort but expressed concerns about how the tests would be implemented.
