<BYLINE>By KATHY EYRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JACKSON, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Highway patrol and sheriff's officers today searched for dozens of children who fled a Baptist boarding home after a judge granted the state temporary custody following allegations of mental and physical abuse. About 80 of approximately 140 children living at the <LOCATION> Bethel </LOCATION> Home for Children in <LOCATION> Lucedale </LOCATION> remained at large, police said late Friday. State officials said they would work over the weekend trying to reach the children's parents and guardians. Youth Court Judge <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Oswald </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Pascagoula </LOCATION> issued the order at 11 a.m. Friday, saying there was probable cause to suspect physical and mental abuse at the home. Minutes after he issued the order, Welfare Department personnel arrived at the home. But in the meantime, the youths apparently were alerted and most had fled. `` We were told they were allowed, if not encouraged, to leave the campus, and some of the children said they were told to run,'' said state Welfare Commissioner <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Brittain </PERSON>. Some of the children, ages 8 through 17, were found in private homes, restaurants and walking along the streets of <LOCATION> Lucedale </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Brittain </PERSON> said. About 60 children were taken to dormitories on the campus of the <ORGANIZATION> Mississippi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION> at <LOCATION> Whitfield </LOCATION>, he said. They were undergoing physical examinations. After the decision was made to house the children at the hospital, parents began calling the hospital, state hospital spokeswoman <PERSON> Wynona </PERSON> <PERSON> Winfield </PERSON> said. Welfare Department social workers, she said, told parents how to get to the hospital, how the children were and answered other questions. Many of the youths were angry as they were taken into custody. `` You have no right, I want to be here with my people,'' said <PERSON> Eric </PERSON> <PERSON> Parker </PERSON>, 16. `` I do n't want to be here with all the rest of you people who hate the truth. You better check yourself and make sure you are not burning on the way to hell.'' Officials were unsure how many children lived at the home because its operator, the Rev. <PERSON> Herman </PERSON> <PERSON> Fountain </PERSON>, refused to provide a list of residents, <PERSON> Brittain </PERSON> said. Fountain, along with several other ministers from the fundamentalist church who flocked from <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> to support him, claim such boarding homes are protected from state regulation because of the constitutional separation of church and state. <PERSON> Oswald </PERSON> issued the order following a weeklong hearing on a request by <LOCATION> George </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> authorities. The hearing stemmed from an investigation into a child who ran away from the home and refused to return, claiming he was physically abused. In court papers, the youth, identified only by his initials, said he was `` tired of being locked up, slapped and getting licks all the time.'' He told social workers he was denied medical and dental treatment during his 19-month stay at the <LOCATION> Bethel </LOCATION> home. Authorities have not charged anyone at the home with abuse but are still investigating the allegations, <PERSON> Brittain </PERSON> said. Telephone calls to the <LOCATION> Bethel </LOCATION> home were not answered late Friday. The judge ruled that according to <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION>'s Youth Act, the children were being held in a detention home rather than a boarding home. Detention facilities are required to notify the state of children placed in their custody. Fountain was jailed for two days for refusing provide a list of residents. But he was freed Friday without turning over the roster after agreeing to an orderly transfer of the children to state custody. When Welfare Department officials arrived, Fountain was already at the home, <PERSON> Brittain </PERSON> said. `` We did not encounter any cooperation from him there. In fact, it was just the opposite,'' <PERSON> Brittain </PERSON> said, declining to elaborate. <PERSON> Brittain </PERSON> said he was unsure whether any action would be taken against Fountain. The court order gives the state 48-hour temporary custody of the children, in addition to custody today and Sunday. Welfare officials hope to locate and return the children to their parents, <PERSON> Brittain </PERSON> said. `` We have information that some folks are trying to help the kids escape out of state,'' he said. Based on his experience with the <LOCATION> Bethesda </LOCATION> Home for Girls near <LOCATION> Hattiesburg </LOCATION>, where about 100 children were taken into state custody in 1986, <PERSON> Brittain </PERSON> said he believed the children's parents would be scattered throughout the country.
