<HEAD>Thousands File Past Coffin of Catalonian Leader</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BARCELONA, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Thousands of people filed past the coffin of <PERSON> Josep </PERSON> <PERSON> Tarradellas </PERSON> today in a final salute to one of the few remaining figures of the ill-fated 1931-1939 Spanish Second Republic. <PERSON> Tarradellas </PERSON>, who became the first head of the restored Catalonian regional government in the post-Franco era, died Friday in this northeastern <LOCATION> Mediterranean </LOCATION> city from complications of a chronic lung ailment. He was 89. Spanish <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Radio </ORGANIZATION> said by midmorning police estimated 3,000 people had filed past <PERSON> Tarradellas </PERSON>' glass-covered coffin draped with the red-and-gold-barred flag of the autonomous region of <LOCATION> Catalonia </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Tarradellas </PERSON> lay in state in the Palace of the Generalitat, the seat of the regional government. The regional government declared three days of mourning for <PERSON> Tarradellas </PERSON>, one of the founders of the <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Left </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Catalonia </LOCATION> in 1931. A government spokesman said a funeral Mass would be held Sunday in <LOCATION> Barcelona </LOCATION> with burial later that day in nearby <LOCATION> Santa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coloma </LOCATION> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Cervello </PERSON>, his hometown. <PERSON> Tarradellas </PERSON> served as a minister of the regional government of <LOCATION> Catalonia </LOCATION> during the 1936-39 Spanish Civil War. He went into exile when the rebel forces of Gen. <PERSON> Francisco </PERSON> <PERSON> Franco </PERSON> defeated troops loyal to the Second Republic. When <PERSON> Tarradellas </PERSON> left <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION> he vowed never to set foot in his native region again until Catalonian autonomy was restored. As the Spanish transition to democracy began upon <PERSON> Franco </PERSON>'s death in 1975, he sought to restore the autonomous government of the four-province northeastern region of <LOCATION> Catalonia </LOCATION>. King <PERSON> Juan </PERSON> <PERSON> Carlos </PERSON> appointed Tarradellas provisional head of the Catalonian government and he returned to <ORGANIZATION> Barcelona </ORGANIZATION> Oct. 23, 1977, where huge crowds were on hand to welcome him home. <PERSON> Tarradellas </PERSON> retired two years later and lived with his wife, <PERSON> Antonia </PERSON>, who survives him.
