<HEAD>Mexico's Papa Panda Suffering from Tumors</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Biopsies have been taken of tumors found in Pe-Pe, the father of <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>'s giant panda family, the director of the <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> zoo said. <PERSON> Maria </PERSON> <PERSON> Helena </PERSON> <PERSON> Hoyo </PERSON>, director of the <ORGANIZATION> Chapultepec </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Zoological </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Garden </ORGANIZATION>, said in a telephone interview Friday that the biopsies were taken Thursday to determine if the tumors are malignant. The results will not be known for at least three weeks, she said. She said doctors removed tissue from Pe-Pe's left armpit and also from the groin area where inflammations of two glands were detected. Experts from the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Zoo </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION>, helped in the operation. Miss <PERSON> Hoyo </PERSON> said the 13-year-old panda `` is in good shape'' and was eating. The tumors were found early this year. In March, Pe-Pe was reported as being lethargic, and his weight had dropped to 249 pounds down his usual 275 to 285 pounds. <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> gave Pe-Pe and his mate, <PERSON> Ying-Ying </PERSON>, to <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> in September 1975. They have produced four cubs through natural conception, the largest such panda family outside <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>.
