<HEAD>West German Company To Pay Millions To Nazi Forced Labor Victims</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 5 grafs to ADD that other German companies have
made similar payments. Pickup 4th graf pvs, ``The announcement...''</NOTE>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Daimler-Benz </ORGANIZATION>, the largest industrial conglomerate in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, will pay $ 11.7 million to victims of Nazi forced labor programs and their families, <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cross </ORGANIZATION> officials announced. <ORGANIZATION> Daimler-Benz </ORGANIZATION> makes cars, buses and <ORGANIZATION> Mercedes-Benz </ORGANIZATION> luxury automobiles, while its wide-ranging subsidiaries also include a major aerospace manufacturer. Like other German companies during <PERSON> Adolf </PERSON> <PERSON> Hitler </PERSON>'s Third Reich, <ORGANIZATION> Daimler </ORGANIZATION> used forced laborers to fuel the Nazi war effort. With the payment, <ORGANIZATION> Daimler-Benz </ORGANIZATION> joins other major German companies who have paid reparations to former forced laborers and their families. In 1986, the giant Flick conglomerate paid $ 2.9 million to slave labor victims. Other West German firms, such as the giant <ORGANIZATION> Krupp </ORGANIZATION> concern, a major weapons producer during World War II, also have paid reparations. The announcement of <ORGANIZATION> Daimler </ORGANIZATION>'s payments follows a lengthy study the company commissioned to determine the extent to which forced laborers worked in its plants nearly a half century ago. Thousands of workers died from ill-treatment or were murdered in concentration camps if they were no longer able to work. The German <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cross </ORGANIZATION>, in a telex statement to the news media on Friday, said it expected to receive $ 2.9 million from the automaker to distribute to forced labor victims in <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Belgium </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Netherlands </LOCATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cross </ORGANIZATION>, located in <LOCATION> Bonn </LOCATION>, said a total of $ 11.7 million would be paid by <ORGANIZATION> Daimler-Benz </ORGANIZATION> to `` those affected and their family members.'' It was not immediately known who would receive the rest of the money, but the <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cross </ORGANIZATION> said in the telex to news media that the donations were all intended for victims and their families living outside <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Daimler-Benz </ORGANIZATION> officials have scheduled a news conference for Monday, at which they were expected to announce further details of the payment plan. They declined to give details of the payment program on Friday.
