<FIRST>r w AM-Ethics     06-11 0330</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Ethics,330</SECOND>
<HEAD>Agency Would Ease Tax Strain for Some Government Officials</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HARRY F. ROSENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A federal agency, seeking to make high-level government service more attractive, is recommending some officials be permitted to postpone taxes on profits resulting from property sold to avoid a conflict of interest with their public duties. The Administrative Conference of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, meeting Thursday and Friday, proposed the deferral of tax liability in cases where the incoming official re-invests the proceeds of the sale in mutual funds. <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> would have to change the tax laws to permit this. The conference, a permanent independent agency established by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to improve the working of federal agencies, proposed that the tax postponement be available only in cases specifically requested by the president. Under current law, officials who are forced to sell off property because they might present conflicts of interest, must pay any capital gains taxes during the year of the sale. `` You should n't have a tax penalty to become a public servant,'' said <PERSON> Fred </PERSON> <PERSON> J </PERSON>. Fielding, a former <ORGANIZATION> Reagan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> counsel who chairs the conference's special committee on ethics in government. The conference also recommended that President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> sign an executive order that later this year would require members of the incoming president's transition team to agree in writing to a code of conduct. During the 1980-1981 presidential transition `` over 600 persons, most serving as volunteers, had active assignments on agency transition teams,'' the group said. While it has no knowledge of any abuse, the group said, so many people dealing with federal agencies `` offers the potential for conflicts of interest or abuse of the public trust that accompanies their special access to government information and facilities.'' The proposed conduct code for transition employees, most of whom are not paid and do not join the government, would prohibit them from using, disclosing or permitting others to use for private gain any information they obtained in their temporary roles.
</TEXT>
