<DATELINE>TUSCALOOSA, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Twenty-five years after he stood face-to-face with <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Wallace </PERSON> at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Alabama </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Nicholas </PERSON> <PERSON> Katzenbach </PERSON> returned to the campus to discuss <PERSON> Wallace </PERSON>'s vain attempt to keep the school segregated <PERSON> Katzenbach </PERSON>, then an assistant <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> attorney general in the <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> administration, was sent to <LOCATION> Tuscaloosa </LOCATION> to enroll two black students against the objections of <PERSON> Wallace </PERSON>, who was governor at the time. A federal court had ordered the students' admission. `` At no time did we really know what Gov. <PERSON> Wallace </PERSON> would do,'' <PERSON> Katzenbach </PERSON> said Friday. `` It made us nervous.'' <PERSON> Katzenbach </PERSON>, now a lawyer in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION>, was among 400 journalists, academics and university alumni who took part in a three-day conference held to commemorate <PERSON> Wallace </PERSON>'s 1963 `` stand in the schoolhouse door.'' <PERSON> Wallace </PERSON>, then serving the first of his four terms, had vowed `` segregation forever'' in his inaugural address, and had promised he would physically prevent any attempt to register blacks at the state university. But <PERSON> Wallace </PERSON>, after a long statement in defiance of the `` central government,'' relented, allowing <PERSON> Vivan </PERSON> <PERSON> Malone </PERSON> and <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Hood </PERSON> to enroll. <PERSON> Wallace </PERSON>, who is wheelchair-bound as the result of an assassination attempt and has made few public appearances since leaving office last year, declined an invitation to attend the conference. An aide, <PERSON> Elvin </PERSON> <PERSON> Stanton </PERSON>, said <PERSON> Wallace </PERSON> would not make a statement about the anniversary. <PERSON> Wallace </PERSON>, who later changed his views on segregation, has said that he made his stand largely to reduce the chances of violence hitting the <LOCATION> Tuscaloosa </LOCATION> campus as it had at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mississippi </ORGANIZATION> earlier.
