re reporting them. He said <ORGANIZATION> VOA </ORGANIZATION> will continue to provide accurate information `` about events which affect them daily, including calls for democracy and freedom.'' The June 2 murder of a graduate student at the university ignited campus protests first of lax security and later of poor living conditions for intellectuals and the slow pace of democratic reform in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>. Dozens of posters, some criticizing the government, were put up and 1,000 students have gathered on a campus square each night to debate political issues and whether they should hold demonstrations. <ORGANIZATION> Xinhua </ORGANIZATION> quoted a student as saying <ORGANIZATION> VOA </ORGANIZATION> is overly interested in bad news about <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>. `` Therefore, I suspect it has the desire to see <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> plunged into chaos,'' the student said. A law student reportedly asked, `` Is the radio not trying to make the situation worse?'' <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s official media have criticized <ORGANIZATION> VOA </ORGANIZATION> for its reports on nationwide pro-democracy student demonstrations in December 1986 and January 1987. The network said its reports were balanced. <ORGANIZATION> VOA </ORGANIZATION>, which broadcasts in Chinese, English and 42 other languages, is a major source of information for students trying to find out what is happening on campuses throughout <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>.
