<SECOND>AM-Sicily-Missiles,0590</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Preparing To Remove Cruise Missiles From Italy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERRY LEONARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COMISO, Sicily (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Russians are coming, and the men and women of the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> 487th Tactical Missile Wing are preparing to show them what few Americans have seen _ 112 cruise missiles. The missiles and their camouflaged launchers, positioned at this base in remote southeastern <LOCATION> Sicily </LOCATION>, are stored under tons of earth and concrete and surrounded by four rows of chain-link fence topped with barbed wire. Soviet inspectors will arrive sometime after July 1 to count the missiles and launchers to be eliminated under terms of the superpower Intermediate-Range Nuclear Force treaty, which went into effect June 1. Lt. Col. <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Wagovich </PERSON>, a spokesman for the <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> On-Site </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inspection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION>, told visiting reporters Friday that over the next three years, the missiles and launchers will be sent to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and destroyed under the eyes of Soviet inspectors. `` Exactly when they are going, or how they are going, I am not at liberty to say,'' he said. <PERSON> Wagovich </PERSON> said the plan is to send the missiles to the <ORGANIZATION> Davis </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mathis </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Base </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Arizona </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> inspectors will monitor the elimination of intermediate range missiles in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Czechoslovakia </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Wagovich </PERSON> said inspection agency officials are working quickly to make sure everything is ready for the Soviets, who can make their first visit between July 1 and the end of August. `` We have had a very short time to recruit and train inspectors and escorts. It has been a very extensive effort. We have conducted mock inspections, testing different scenarios,'' said <PERSON> Wagovich </PERSON>. Two Soviet reporters already have visited this high-security base. They came Friday with other reporters from <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>. Soviet and East-bloc journalists have also been shown missile bases in <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Belgium </LOCATION>. Western reporters visited a Soviet base in the northern republic of <LOCATION> Ukraine </LOCATION> on June 3. During the visit to <PERSON> Comiso </PERSON>, Capt. <PERSON> Don </PERSON> <PERSON> Sparks </PERSON> demonstrated how the launchers are raised and prepared for action. But the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> did not allow reporters to see a cruise missile. Each of the mobile launchers can fire four 21-foot missiles that can deliver a 200-kiloton nuclear warhead 1,500 miles at almost the speed of sound. The atomic bomb dropped on <LOCATION> Hiroshima </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, in 1945 had an explosive force of 20 kilotons. <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> officials, citing security reasons, declined to discuss the number of warheads at Comiso or their total destructive force. The Italian government agreed in 1982 to take the missiles, and <PERSON> Comiso </PERSON> became the second base in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> to accept cruise missiles. The first were located at <LOCATION> Greenham </LOCATION> Common, <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> officials estimate that the base _ a mostly treeless 379-acre expanse of asphalt, sun-baked earth and brown and beige stucco buildings _ pumps $ 18.2 million a year into the local economy. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and Italian officials said no decision has been made on how to use the base once the missiles have left or on what to do with the 1,750 American and 179 Italian military personnel. Americans first came to this base 45 years ago. On July 11, 1943, <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> troops commanded by Lt. Gen. <PERSON> Omar </PERSON> <PERSON> Bradley </PERSON> captured the Axis airfield after Allied bombers hammered the base. Six days later, Allied fighter planes began to use the air base.
