<HEAD>Pakistan Rejects Allegations of Geneva Accord Violations</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED AFTAB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> on Saturday denied allegations that it is violating a U.N.-sponsored accord on the Afghan war by aiding Afghan guerrillas. It also claimed that <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> had made forays into its airspace and territory. `` The allegations made by the <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> side were rejected, and a point by point reply has been handed over to the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION>,'' said a Foreign Ministry official, who spoke on condition of anonymity. The Pakistani official said the reply `` emphasized ... that <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> can not be held responsible'' for guerrilla actions against the <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> government inside <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>. `` <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> is also not expected to prohibit the legitimate political activity of the Afghan refugees who represent a substantial segment of the Afghan population,'' the spokesman said. The <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> sponsored an accord calling for withdrawal from <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> of the Soviet troops helping the <LOCATION> Afghan </LOCATION> government in its 10-year-old war with anti-communist guerrillas. <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> signed the accord in <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> on April 14. <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> repeatedly has charged that <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> is violating the agreement, which took effect May 15, by continuing to arm guerrillas. Soviet Foreign Minister <PERSON> Eduard </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shevardnadze </PERSON> made the same charge at the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> on Friday and said the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATI