<SECOND>AM-North Dakota Lottery,0674</SECOND>
<HEAD>Proposed Lottery Faces Different Sort Of Opposition in Second
Go-Round</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DALE WETZEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BISMARCK, N.D. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A former governor fighting to defeat a state lottery initiative for the second time in as many years has picked up an unlikely ally _ representatives of the state's multimillion-dollar gambling industry `` They just happen to be on the same side that we've been on since the proposal on lotteries has started,'' said <PERSON> Arthur </PERSON> <PERSON> Link </PERSON>, a former congressman who was <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dakota </LOCATION> governor from 1972 to 1980. `` I do n't think it's ironic.'' Lined up in opposition with Link, who opposes a state lottery as a regressive tax on poorer citizens, are charities that are allowed to run casino gambling in <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dakota </LOCATION>. The proposal's primary backer predicts the measure will succeed this year, helped by increased public awareness of flourishing lotteries in neighboring <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dakota </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Montana </LOCATION>. `` Good God, we're the only one left,'' says <PERSON> Gorman </PERSON> <PERSON> King </PERSON> <PERSON> Sr. </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Mandan </LOCATION> businessman who is spearheading the pro-lottery effort. Twenty-six states and the <LOCATION> District </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION> are operating lotteries, and <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> are scheduled to start them this summer. Voters in neighboring <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION> are to decide in November whether to allow one. <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dakota </LOCATION> is the only state that has voted down a state-run lottery. Voters will cast ballots in Tuesday's primary on whether to approve a state lottery, which is now banned by the state Constitution. The state's voters first rejected a lottery almost a century ago, after gambling interests attempted to bribe the Legislature into starting one. The constitution was changed recently to allow `` public-spirited organizations'' to run gambling casinos, and more than 300 groups, ranging from humane societies to <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Legion </ORGANIZATION> posts, offer bingo, blackjack and other games to benefit a variety of charities. North Dakotans spent $ 189.2 million on charitable gambling last year, and once prizes, taxes and allowable expenses were deducted, charities netted slightly more than $ 17 million in 1987, according to the most recent attorney general's report. Critics contend a lottery would lure away the discretionary cash <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dakotans </LOCATION> now use for bingo and blackjack and thus hurt the charities. `` It could have a direct effect on the organizations that are trying to continue to fund their programs,'' said R.S. <PERSON> Guilderhus </PERSON>, executive director of the Fargo-based <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> River </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Human </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foundation </ORGANIZATION>. A lottery could conceivably drain away 70 to 80 percent of the $ 500,000 in annual gambling proceeds his foundation now spends on services, <PERSON> Gilderhus </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Winston </PERSON> <PERSON> Satran </PERSON>, director of the Home on the Range for Boys near <LOCATION> Sentinel </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Butte </LOCATION> in extreme western <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dakota </LOCATION>, said about 15 percent of the ranch's private donations come from fraternal organizations that raise money from gambling. `` I think those -LRB- lottery -RRB- dollars would be diverted from what is being spent on charitable gambling now,'' he said. King estimates a <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dakota </LOCATION> lottery would gross $ 20 million annually, with half of that sum returned to players as prizes. Of the remainder, $ 7 million, or 35 percent, would go to the state general fund; 10 percent would pay for lottery expenses; and 5 percent would go to vendors as commissions. `` It would be that much less that -LRB- the <ORGANIZATION> Legislature </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- would be in your pocket for,'' <PERSON> King </PERSON> said of the projected $ 7 million in proceeds. `` And it's a voluntary tax. It's up to you whether you want to do it or not.'' Link, a longtime friend of King, contends a lottery amounts to a regressive tax on lower-income people and that its benefits would be outweighed by its potential social costs. A lottery also represents a step beyond the existing charitable gambling industry, said Link. `` This changes the role of government completely, in that it puts the state government as the official promoter,'' <PERSON> Link </PERSON> said. `` The state ... is encouraging its own citizens to buy into a game of chance where most of them have to lose. That's not the role of state government.''
