<FIRST>r w BC-DemocratsText     06-11 0666</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Democrats Text,650</SECOND>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Here is the text of the <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>'s response to President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s weekly radio address Saturday, given by Rep. <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Gephardt </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Missouri </LOCATION>: Since 1981, we've seen our trade deficit skyrocket more than four times over We've seen millions of manufacturing jobs lost and thousands of farmers thrown off their land. During these years, the president has stood idly by, failing to develop a trade policy to enhance American competitiveness. He even called our trade deficit a sign of strength. Three years ago, the Democrats took the bull by the horns and crafted a trade policy that would enhance our competitiveness. We fought for fundamental change in our trade policy and were able to forge a consensus, at least among Democrats, about what we must do to do compete, strengthen education, improve productivity, and invest in plan and equipment and people. The human factor would be the most decisive factor of production. In a historic effort, Democrats working with Republicans were able to craft a bill. It took three years and countless discussions to write. It was designed to put the tools in the hands of our workers and businesses, to improve our competitiveness and pry open markets. Despite the strong support for the bill, President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> vetoed the measure. In doing so, he deprived us of the trade policy we so desperately need. President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> based his veto on his objection to the plant closing provision in the bill _ a provision which he claims will hurt business and had nothing to do with trade. <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> needs the plant closing law. If we're going to prepare for the future rather than protect against it, we must give our workers the time needed to adjust and find new employment. It's a simple provision. It requires management to give workers a 60-day notice of impending plant closure _ nothing more, nothing less. During my travels across the country, I met countless workers who had suffered from the lack of a plant-closing provision. There is simply no justification for a worker showing up at the plant gate for work to find it chained shut. Many businesses have joined with the president in fighting the provision. At the same time they have fought for their own golden parachute and 60-day notification for themselves in hostile takeover situations. They refuse to grant workers the same consideration.. I refuse to accept the president's notion that people can be treated just like any other asset, to be discarded when no longer needed. Our workers are the best in the world. They've proven their ability to adapt to change. In many cases, labor and management working together have been able to find solutions to the company's problems The plant closing provision is an investment in our people. It's unfortunate that the president chose to scuttle the trade bill because of his opposition to this provision We desperately need a trade bill. Trade is not an academic issue; it is a human issue. We cant continue to follow the course set by this administration. We've seen our position as the world's largest creditor nation erode to that of the largest debtor. We continue to run historic trade deficits. Behind these numbers are real people _ business people and workers who've seen their companies go under because of unfair foreign competition, farmers who have lost their farms because they ca n't sell their products overseas. It's time for a change in our trade policy to put our economic ship of state back on course. The plain and painful fact is that without any incentive for reciprocity many of our trading partners are using our outdated assumptions to take advantage of us. We've got to realize that the world has changed and we must change with it Mr. President, the trade deficit is not a sign of strength; it's a sign of a failed policy We must now work together to change that policy and make <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> strong again.
