<HEAD>Deputy Suspended Because Her Fingernails Are Too Long</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A sheriff's deputy whose fingernails are a quarter-inch over regulation was suspended for four days after she refused to trim them, saying she's had them long all her 10 years on the job and they do n't interfere with her work. <PERSON> Danielle </PERSON> <PERSON> Rogers </PERSON>, who works at the <LOCATION> Hennepin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> juvenile center, has nails that are three-eighths inch past her fingertips. A grooming policy adopted by the sheriff's department May 16 says nails may not be longer than an eighth of an inch. The policy covers a range of subjects, including the length and style of hair, personal hygiene and wearing jewelry. <ORGANIZATION> Rogers </ORGANIZATION> filed a grievance over the policy, claiming it is an issue that should have been decided in collective bargaining between department officials and the deputies' union. She was suspended Wednesday for a day for violating the rule, and again on Thursday, this time for three days, for not trimming her nails. On Friday, the union filed suit against <LOCATION> Hennepin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> and Sheriff <PERSON> Don </PERSON> <PERSON> Omodt </PERSON>, claiming that the failure to negotiate the policy was an unfair labor practice and that <PERSON> Rogers </PERSON> was disciplined for exercising her right to file a grievance. <LOCATION> Hennepin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Ann </PERSON> <PERSON> Montgomery </PERSON> denied a temporary restraining order Friday and scheduled a hearing for Monday on whether a preliminary injunction should be issued. <PERSON> Omodt </PERSON> did not return a telephone call to the department Saturday. His home telephone is unlisted. In an affidavit filed with the court, <PERSON> Rogers </PERSON> said she has had her nails the same length for the 10 years she has worked as a deputy and they do not affect her work. The objection is not over the grooming policy, said her attorney, <PERSON> Marshall </PERSON> <PERSON> Tanick </PERSON>, but over the failure of the county to bargain with the union. He also said there is a right to privacy in personal appearance as long as it is not detrimental to the job. Another problem with the policy, <PERSON> Tanick </PERSON> said, is that it does not spell out what the consequences are for violating it. <ORGANIZATION> Rogers </ORGANIZATION> has been threatened with disciplinary action up to dismissal, according to court documents. <PERSON> Karla </PERSON> <PERSON> Hancock </PERSON>, assistant <LOCATION> Hennepin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> attorney, said Friday there was no need to bargain about the policy because it falls under management's rights, rather than being a term and condition of employment that must be negotiated. Said <PERSON> Tanick </PERSON>: `` We believe there are serious law enforcement issues in the county that merit attention. Too much time and energy has been devoted to this petty issue. `` As long as the deputy is competent, the length of her nails should not matter.''
