<HEAD>Rapidly Changing China Leaves Maoist Ideology Behind</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM ABRAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 In <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, a nation that takes its political slogans seriously, a large billboard in a provincial capital, reading `` Efficiency Is Life _ Time Is Money,'' is a dramatic sign of the times. It is an indication of how <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> ideologists, the shapers of public opinion, have been backed into a corner by the rapid acceptance of private ownership, shareholding and free markets _ all capitalistic challenges to Marxist-Leninist doctrine. `` Capitalism has absorbed things from socialism _ now we should absorb some good things from capitalism,'' said <PERSON> Zhao </PERSON> <PERSON> Yao </PERSON>, dean of the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION>, a training ground for ideologists. Capitalism was once dismissed in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> as an evil opposed to socialism. `` But we now believe that was wrong,'' added <PERSON> Zhao </PERSON>. The official doctrines that have often forced the Chinese to worry about whether they are being good communists have been in a state of flux since <PERSON> Deng </PERSON> <PERSON> Xiaoping </PERSON>, the pragmatist famed for saying, `` It does n't matter if a cat is black or white, as long as it catches mice,'' came to power 10 years ago. Declaring that `` poverty is not socialism,'' he dismantled <PERSON> Mao </PERSON> <PERSON> Tse-tung </PERSON>'s communes, restored the profit motive and unleashed free-market forces into a rigid system of central planning. Today, the concern of most Chinese is how to get better wages and cope with rising prices. `` As long as the economy is prosperous and living standards are raised, our purpose is fulfilled,'' said <PERSON> Li </PERSON> <PERSON> Yining </PERSON>, a prominent economist. This month, the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> will publish its last issue of the journal `` Red Flag,'' whose heavy prose has for 30 years set the tone for party ideology. In its place, the party will inaugurate a publication called `` Seeking Truth,'' which is expected to concentrate on economic reforms and political democratization. Party leader <PERSON> Zhao </PERSON> <PERSON> Ziyang </PERSON>, a major supporter of economic reforms, announced at a party conference last fall that <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> will be in what he called the `` primary stage'' of socialism through the middle of the next century. <PERSON> Zhao </PERSON> told economic planners they would be allowed to adapt capitalist practices as long as these advanced the national goal of economic development. Party propagandists hailed <PERSON> Zhao </PERSON>'s laissez-faire approach to socialism, which played down the need for ideology to back up policy The Guangming Daily, <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s leading intellectual newspaper, said in a recent commentary that great changes have taken place in the past decade. `` However, we can not deny that in many places dogmatism, like a specter, still binds the people's thinking and hampers the development of socialist modernization,'' it said, adding that even these days, almost every new economic or political reform must still overcome suspicions of being too `` capitalistic.'' By adopting unorthodox approaches to Marxism and capitalism, the new theorists are trying to legitimize reforms that have brought <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> television commercials promoting consumption, free markets taking away business from state stores, and millionaires with servants. Many of the new theorists say the ideology of <PERSON> Karl </PERSON> <PERSON> Marx </PERSON>, who lived in the 19th century, can not explain the modern relationship between socialism and capitalism. They say <PERSON> Mao </PERSON>'s insistence on class struggle over economic development was a disaster for <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>. Leading social scientist <PERSON> Li </PERSON> <PERSON> Honglin </PERSON> recently wrote that the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> _ once <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s model as an economic system _ has failed to match the productive energy of capitalist countries. `` Socialism is not a cake that can be ordered, and there is no fixed pattern for socialism,'' <PERSON> Li </PERSON> wrote. `` To promote reforms we must make breakthroughs in theory,'' said <PERSON> Zhao </PERSON> <PERSON> Yao </PERSON>, dean of the <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION>. Shareholding, private ownership of property and even the democratic process are other Western practices that can be of use to Chinese socialism, the party school theorists said. <PERSON> Zhao </PERSON> said <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s 18 million private entrepreneurs have become `` an important auxiliary part'' of the economy. But the party theorists insist that <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> remain a socialist country whose vital task is to define socialism to meet the country's changing needs. Reflecting this task, the <ORGANIZATION> Chinese </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Academy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Social </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Science </ORGANIZATION> has said it will this year start a new research project _ the study of a modified form of socialism. The head of the research team will be one of <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s most progressive political thinkers, <PERSON> Su </PERSON> <PERSON> Shaozhi </PERSON>, who a year ago was fired from his position as head of the academy's <ORGANIZATION> Marxism-Leninism </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> for being too liberal.
