<HEAD>Graham Preaches as Christian Celebration Continues in Soviet Union</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Rev. <PERSON> Billy </PERSON> <PERSON> Graham </PERSON> brought his impassioned brand of preaching to a church packed with Russian Orthodox believers on Saturday, but the evangelist's fire-and-brimstone delivery failed to ignite his listeners. <PERSON> Graham </PERSON>'s appearance was part of this communist country's celebration of the 1,000 th anniversary of the arrival of `` Some things change, some things never change,'' <PERSON> Graham </PERSON> told the crowd gathered in the 17th-century Church of <LOCATION> Our </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lady </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kazan </LOCATION> at <LOCATION> Kolomenskoye </LOCATION> in southern <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>. `` God never changes. Human nature never changes.'' `` Your liturgy is based on the Bible. And the Bible says that the world will be shaken from time to time,'' <PERSON> Graham </PERSON> said, clearly alluding to the social changes that Soviet leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> is attempting through his reforms. <PERSON> Graham </PERSON>, a Southern Baptist evangelist, was in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> as part of the officially sanctioned celebration of the introduction of Christianity into <LOCATION> Russia </LOCATION> by Prince <PERSON> Vladimir </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Kiev </LOCATION> in 988. <PERSON> Graham </PERSON>'s English-language sermon was translated into Russian by the Rev. <PERSON> Vladimir </PERSON> <PERSON> Sorokin </PERSON>, head of the Russian Orthodox seminary in the northern Russian city of <LOCATION> Leningrad </LOCATION>. The Soviet congregation reacted coolly to <PERSON> Graham </PERSON>'s sermon, only waving their hands when he asked at one point if they were happy. A few clapped politely as he was driven away from the church in a government-owned black <LOCATION> Chaika </LOCATION>. `` It was strange,'' one woman told another as the worshipers filed from the church and mingled with those who had not been able to find room inside. Blue-shirted uniformed police officers were scattered at the edge of the grounds but made no move to interfere with the proceedings. Soviet authorities brutally repressed the church in the years after the 1917 Bolshevik Revolution, especially under <PERSON> Josef </PERSON> <PERSON> V. </PERSON> <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON>, jailing or killing many priests and nationalizing church property. Until recently, police surrounded churches on such religious holidays as Easter, allowing only the elderly to enter. Under <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>, the state has returned to the church the Monastery of the Caves in <LOCATION> Kiev </LOCATION>, agreed to build an old-age home for priests, and promised to liberalize a 1929 law which sanctioned suppression of the church. In another sign of relaxation, authorities on Friday released a Russian Orthodox deacon, <PERSON> Vasily </PERSON> <PERSON> Shipilov </PERSON>, who spent 36 of his 60 years in psychiatric prisons. Signals that authorities will moderate constraints on the church have aroused mixed reactions among visiting clergymen. <PERSON> Graham </PERSON>, who said during a 1982 visit that he thought the church in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> was free, this time said only that `` the people seem to be warmer. That makes me glad,'' according to his spokesman, <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Plowman </PERSON>. <PERSON> Graham </PERSON> did not speak with reporters at Saturday's service. Cardinal <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Connor </PERSON> of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> said Friday, `` I think anyone in his right mind prays that Mr. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> is sincere and wants to bring about a new era.'' <PERSON> O'Connor </PERSON>, the highest-ranking American in the largest <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION> delegation ever to visit the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, was scheduled to attend an evening religious vigil Saturday night. That service is in preparation for the celebration Sunday of one of the holiest dates on the Russian Orthodox calendar, known as `` Sunday of All the <ORGANIZATION> Saints </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Who </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Shone </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forth </ORGANIZATION> in the Land of <LOCATION> Russia </LOCATION>.'' Soviet President <PERSON> Andrei </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gromyko </PERSON>, whose prominence in the Soviet government dates to the <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON> era, met Saturday at the <LOCATION> Kremlin </LOCATION> with foreign religious dignitaries who are in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> for the church millennium. <PERSON> Gromyko </PERSON> assured his guests that authorities were working quickly to redraft the law on religion to guarantee greater tolerance of believers, the official <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> news agency said.
