<HEAD>Catholics Rally Behind Defiant Cardinal at Consecration</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By IVA DRAPALOVA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 About 5,000 Roman Catholics packed St. Vitus Cathedral on Saturday for the consecration of two assistant bishops, the first such appointments allowed by communist authorities since 1973. Catholics seized the opportunity to show their support for defiant Cardinal <PERSON> Frantisek </PERSON> <PERSON> Tomasek </PERSON>, the archbishop of <LOCATION> Prague </LOCATION> and the Catholic primate of <LOCATION> Czechoslovakia </LOCATION>. After the ceremony, hundreds of believers massed at the entrance to the archbishop's palace, shouting `` We want religious freedom!,'' `` Long live father cardinal!'' and `` Long live the pope!'' <PERSON> Tomasek </PERSON> has come under strong attack from state-run news media this year for supporting a petition for more religious freedom, which has been signed by an estimated 600,000 people. Saturday's ceremony was the first public consecration of assistant bishops in <LOCATION> Prague </LOCATION> in 55 years and was marked by repeated calls for more bishops denied by the communist regime. <PERSON> Tomasek </PERSON> officiated at what was a major church gathering to celebrate the formal appointment of <PERSON> Jan </PERSON> <PERSON> Lebeda </PERSON>, the 75-year-old vicar general of <LOCATION> Prague </LOCATION> and 64-year-old <PERSON> Antonin </PERSON> <PERSON> Liska </PERSON> as assistant bishops of <LOCATION> Prague </LOCATION>. The state was represented by Minister of Education <PERSON> Milan </PERSON> <PERSON> Kymlicka </PERSON> and officials of the state church authority, but not by <PERSON> Vladimir </PERSON> <PERSON> Janku </PERSON>, the head of the department. The first churchman to speak was parish priest <PERSON> Karel </PERSON> <PERSON> Otcenasek </PERSON> from <LOCATION> Trmice </LOCATION> in northern <LOCATION> Bohemia </LOCATION>, who was consecrated as bishop in 1951 at age 29 but was never permitted by the authorities to take up office. In his address, frequently interrupted by applause, <PERSON> Otcenasek </PERSON> assured the cardinal: `` You feel the difficulties and fears of us all. ... The church in our country speaks in a single voice and that comes out of your mouth.'' In April, the cardinal wrote to Premier <PERSON> Lubomir </PERSON> <PERSON> Strougal </PERSON> urging that the church and the authorities open a new dialogue. The offer was rejected amid indications the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> is reinforcing its atheist drive. <PERSON> Tomasek </PERSON> said in his short sermon, `` We expect this to be only the beginning of further consecrations of bishops. Nine dioceses have been waiting a long number of years for their diocesan bishops.''. Ten bishoprics in all have been reported to be vacant. <PERSON> Tomasek </PERSON>'s mentioning nine apparently has to do with one bishopric being Greek Orthodox The event was attended by bishops from <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Austria </LOCATION>. After the ceremony, papal emissary Archbishop <PERSON> Francesco </PERSON> <PERSON> Colasuonno </PERSON> addressed the congregation in Czech, assuring the faithful of `` church solidarity.'' Later, the faithful lined up six deep along the short route to the archbishop's palace, cheering church dignitaries as they were driven by. They then gathered in front of the palace, shouting their support for the cardinal and for religious freedom and singing hymns. The crowd dispersed peacefully after about 45 minutes. Police looked on but did not interfere.
