said. <PERSON> Genscher </PERSON>'s speech marked the first time a West German leader of <PERSON> Genscher </PERSON>'s rank made an official address in <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Genscher </PERSON>, who left <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> in 1952, made several references to World War II as well as to atrocities that occurred during <PERSON> Adolf </PERSON> <PERSON> Hitler </PERSON>'s rule of <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>. `` It is obvious that we Germans bear a special responsibility for overcoming the division of our continent,'' <PERSON> Genscher </PERSON> said. `` The bitter experiences of this century prompt those nations to keep a watchful eye on us Germans.'' <PERSON> Genscher </PERSON> spoke out strongly for a `` common European house.'' `` We Germans must render a major contribution to building confidence between East and West. We want to re-activate the once so varied and fruitful bonds between Germans and Russians. We want to develop and deepen them with the aim of overcoming the division in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Genscher </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Genscher </PERSON> also praised the reforms of Soviet leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> and rejected any suggestion that increased East-West cooperation could `` decouple the <LOCATION> European </LOCATION> allies.''
