<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Cavalrymen and foot soldiers in scarlet tunics and bearskin hats paraded in the center of <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> Saturday to honor Queen <PERSON> Elizabeth </PERSON> <PERSON> II </PERSON> with the Trooping the Color on her `` official'' birthday. The queen, who is 62, celebrated her real birthday on April 21, but the official birthday ceremonies are held on the second Saturday of June when the weather normally is better. The sky was overcast and there was a damp chill in the air Saturday. This year, for the first time since 1973, the 1,588 men of all five regiments of the Brigade of Guards joined the parade because all are currently based in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>. The guards _ Grenadier, Coldstream, <ORGANIZATION> Scots </ORGANIZATION>, Irish and Welsh regiments _ are often scattered, seeing service in such places as <LOCATION> Northern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Falkland </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Islands </LOCATION>. Four generations of the royal family joined the ceremony this year, riding in coaches or on horseback to the Horse Guards Parade, an open square in <ORGANIZATION> Whitehall </ORGANIZATION>, where the queen inspected the Irish Guards while massed bands played. Each year one regiment performs the honors, marching in intricate patterns and carrying the `` color,'' or regimental standard. <PERSON> Elizabeth </PERSON>, wearing a blue coat and wide-brimmed hat, arrived in a horse-drawn phaeton and took the salute standing on a dais. It was the second year she had used the carriage since retiring her horse, <LOCATION> Burmese </LOCATION>, which she used to ride sidesaddle for the occasion, wearing a scarlet uniform. The queen's 5-year-old grandson, <PERSON> Prince </PERSON> <PERSON> William </PERSON>, was with his mother, the Princess <PERSON> Diana </PERSON>, and his great-grandmother, Queen <PERSON> Mother </PERSON> <PERSON> Elizabeth </PERSON>, in her carriage. Riding horseback was the heir to the throne, <PERSON> Prince </PERSON> <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> in his uniform as colonel of the Welsh Guards, along with the queen's husband, <PERSON> Prince </PERSON> <PERSON> Philip </PERSON>, a colonel of the Grenadier Guards On her return to <LOCATION> Buckingham </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Palace </LOCATION>, the queen appeared on a balcony to wave to her subjects and thousands of tourists. Saturday's pageantry was based on the ceremony used for guard mounting in the 18th century and was first performed on the sovereign's birthday for King <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON>. But during the 18th and 19th centuries the trooping was seldom attended by the monarch. In 1895, the color was trooped in the quadrangle at <LOCATION> Windsor </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Castle </LOCATION>, west of <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, and <PERSON> Queen </PERSON> <PERSON> Victoria </PERSON> took the salute from a carriage. From that year on, a senior royal person has always been in attendance.
