ujuvenation process in the academy began in December, when 255 new academicians and lesser-ranking corresponding members were elected at a two-day meeting of the academy's membership. Many newcomers were from 40 to 45 years old. New rules were put into effect last year requiring academicians to retire at age 75. <PERSON> Semyonov </PERSON> said `` the renewal of personnel in the academy would go on,'' <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> reported. He said 20 directors, three deputy directors and 160 heads of subdivisions still hold their positions despite their `` advanced age.'' The academy in the past has jealously guarded its integrity even at the risk of incurring political displeasure. It insists on holding its elections by secret ballot, when other Soviet organizations vote by a public show of hands. Physicist and human rights activist <PERSON> Andrei </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Sakharov </PERSON>, an academy member, was stripped of state honors and privileges after becoming active in the Soviet dissident movement of the 1970s. But academy members refused to oust him, and he kept his title of academician even after being exiled to Gorky in 1980. In December 1986, <PERSON> Sakharov </PERSON>, 67, was allowed to return to <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> to resume his research work in physics.
