<HEAD>Tests Show Waste Dumped Near Nigerian Port Is Toxic</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LAGOS, Nigeria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Preliminary tests show that waste secretly dumped in eastern Nigerian by an Italian company is toxic, the military government announced Saturday. The <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nigeria </ORGANIZATION> said Saturday that the dump site, near the port of <LOCATION> Koko </LOCATION>, had become somewhat of a tourist attraction, with Nigerians flocking to the area to see the waste. Earlier it was reported that security agents had sealed off the area, 150 miles southeast of <LOCATION> Lagos </LOCATION>. Scientists urged that anyone who visited the site seek medical tests. The dumping episode, the latest in a series of alleged efforts by European and American companies to dump hazardous waste in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>, has strained relations between <LOCATION> Nigeria </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>. On Friday, the government seized the Italian ship Piave in <LOCATION> Lagos </LOCATION> harbor and said it would be required to remove poisonous waste dumped in eastern <LOCATION> Nigeria </LOCATION>. Earlier, <LOCATION> Nigeria </LOCATION> recalled its ambassador from <LOCATION> Rome </LOCATION>. Nigerian government spokesman <PERSON> Yusufu </PERSON> <PERSON> Mamman </PERSON> said Nigerians and Italians were arrested in the case. He did not identify them. On Saturday, the Italian news agency <ORGANIZATION> ANSA </ORGANIZATION>, reporting from <LOCATION> Trieste </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>, quoted an official of the LLoyd Triestino shipping company, <PERSON> Ennio </PERSON> <PERSON> Vasta </PERSON>, as saying the <PERSON> Piave </PERSON> did not carry toxic wastes. <PERSON> Vasta </PERSON> was quoted as saying the Piave carried food products, home appliances, machinery and shoes and `` has nothing to do, in absolutely no manner, with toxic wastes.'' He was quoted as saying the Nigerians are pretending the Piave came loa