<HEAD>Runoff Vote For A New National Assembly Sunday</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFFREY ULBRICH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 French voters on Sunday choose a new National Assembly that either will give President <PERSON> Francois </PERSON> <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON> a Socialist majority or force him to continue `` cohabitation'' with the right. Five weeks after <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON> won re-election with a solid 54 percent of the vote over conservative former Premier <PERSON> Jacques </PERSON> <PERSON> Chirac </PERSON>, the Socialist position appeared to be eroding and what once was seen as a leftist landslide in the Assembly voting has become a contest. The Socialists recently talked about giving away constituencies to centrists as part of their `` opening'' to non-Socialists, but they now are fighting for every seat and acknowledging the possiblity of defeat. Despite polling fewer popular votes nationwide than conservatives in the first round, the Socialists are given the edge to win a majority in the Assembly because of peculiarities in the spread of their support. Publication of polls is prohibited by law in the week before an election, but unpublished surveys indicate a Socialist advantage. In the first round of the legislative elections on June 5, the Socialists won 40 of the 577 seats in the Assembly and the Communists won one. On the right, the conservative Rally for the Republic and center-right <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> French </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democracy </ORGANIZATION> won 77 seats and minor rightist parties four. Sunday's runoffs are being held in the 453 districts where no candidate won a majority in the first round. In addition, a first round is being held for two seats in <LOCATION> French </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Polynesia </LOCATION>. In districts where no candidate won a majority in the first round, all candidates with 12.5 percent or more were eligible for the runoff. As they have done in past years, the <ORGANIZATION> Socialist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> agreed to support the leading leftist candidate. In districts where the <ORGANIZATION> Socialist </ORGANIZATION> candidate was ahead, the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> candidate withdrew, and vice versa. The event of the week was the traditional right's similar deal with the extreme right <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION>, the party accused by nearly all political leaders of being racist and xenophobic. Though involving only a small number of seats, the left immediately seized on the issue and accused the Rally for the Republic and Union for French Democracy of signing a pact with the devil. For <PERSON> Jean-Marie </PERSON> <PERSON> Le </PERSON> <PERSON> Pen </PERSON>'s <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION>, it's the difference between being shut out of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION> altogether and winning some seats. For the traditional right, it could be the difference between being in power or in the opposition. The Rally for the Republic and <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> French </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democracy </ORGANIZATION> denied there was any `` deal'' with the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION>. From 1981 to 1986, the Socialists had absolute power. In 1986, after the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION>'s five-year term expired, the right won a slim majority. But because <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON> had two years left on his seven-year term, the right and the left were forced into `` cohabitation,'' or power-sharing. The politicians hated cohabitation. But numerous polls indicated voters liked the balance of power between the right and the left. Analysts said <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON>'s score was due to his personal popularity and not necessarily an indication French voters want a return to leftist policies. On the other hand, his solid victory did create a certain momentum. The president said recently he thought it unhealthy for one party to have all the power in <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>. Nonetheless, sensing his party was in trouble, he went on national television Thursday to ask voters to give him a clear majority with which to work in Parliament. As in the presidential campaign, not much attention has been paid to the issues. With all of the talk focusing on the `` opening'' and the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION>, little concrete has been said about unemployment, social security or education. The French may be tired of voting. Turnout during last week's first round was 65.74 percent _ a postwar low
