<HEAD>Booze From Great Lakes Shipwreck Finds Buyers 75 Years Later</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Scotch whisky and scotch cq as AP style. Whyte &amp; Mackay
Scotch Whiskey cq in brand name.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CHARLES J. GANS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Tipplers with a thirst for treasure got a chance Saturday to bid at an auction of bottles of scotch and champagne recovered from a <LOCATION> Great </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lakes </LOCATION> shipwreck 75 years ago. <PERSON> Susie </PERSON> <PERSON> Shaw </PERSON> bought her dad some Scotch whisky for a Father's Day present, three bottles that had been slowly vintaging in the cool waters of <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Huron </LOCATION> since the <ORGANIZATION> S.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Regina </ORGANIZATION> went down on Nov. 9, 1913. `` It tastes very good,'' said Ms. <PERSON> Shaw </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>, who paid $ 180 for the bottles of <ORGANIZATION> Whyte </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Mackay </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Scotch </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Whiskey </ORGANIZATION> and sampled some of the lake-bed booze at a pre-auction tasting session. `` It's a novelty, my father is a scotch drinker.'' So far, about 300 bottles of French champagne and Scotch whisky have been salvaged from the <PERSON> Regina </PERSON>, one of 19 ships that went down in the great November storm. Several thousand more bottles still rest under 80 feet of water roughly 3 -LCB- miles offshore from <LOCATION> Port </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sanilac </LOCATION>, about 80 miles northeast of <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION>, said commercial diver <PERSON> Wayne </PERSON> <PERSON> Brusate </PERSON>. Brusate accidentally discovered the wreck in July 1986 while searching for a tugboat that sank in the late 1960s. `` I was surprised to find the cases of liquor,'' said <PERSON> Brusate </PERSON>, of <LOCATION> Marysville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mich. </LOCATION> `` Most freighters on the Great Lakes carried coal, iron ore and tons of wheat, but this was like a general store.'' The <PERSON> Regina </PERSON>, a 249-foot Canadian freighter, went down with all 27 crew members during one of the worst storms in Great Lakes history. `` You can buy scotch anywhere, but only here can you buy it from the lake bottom,'' said <PERSON> Deanna </PERSON> <PERSON> Chan </PERSON>, president of <ORGANIZATION> Freedom </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Marine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ltd. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Vancouver </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> British </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION>, the ship's salvagers. `` It's a piece of our history, a collector's item.'' About 100 people attended Saturday's auction, run by <PERSON> Christie </PERSON>'s auctioneers, at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Club </ORGANIZATION> in downtown <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> <PERSON> Brent </PERSON> <PERSON> Albrecht </PERSON>, a representative of <ORGANIZATION> Clicquot </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>. <LOCATION> U.S.A. </LOCATION>, bid $ 85 for a bottle of 1906-1908 vintage <ORGANIZATION> Veuve </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Clicquot </ORGANIZATION> for the champagne company's museum in <LOCATION> Reims </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> The 60 bottles auctioned brought a total of $ 3,460, said <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Davis </PERSON>, vice-president of <PERSON> Christie </PERSON>'s wine division. `` This was sort of a first for us, an experiment,'' he said. `` We are neither disappointed or ecstatic, because there's no real track record for this. We're glad the bottles found buyers.'' In December, the first auction of <PERSON> Regina </PERSON> artifacts in <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION> found bidders paying $ 15 - $ 35 for lumps of coal, matchsticks, and spoons, Ms. <PERSON> Chan </PERSON> said At a marine auction on Sunday in <LOCATION> Newport </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> R.I. </LOCATION>, the ship's compass, navigation lights and other nautical equipment were to be sold The proceeds will help finance further salvage operations which are scheduled to resume next month, <PERSON> Brusate </PERSON> said. He estimated that only about 10 percent of the ship's cargo has been recovered so far. The search will concentrate on finding the ship's safe, which reportedly contained $ 86,000 in gold coins, worth at least $ 2 million at current bullion prices, Ms. <PERSON> Chan </PERSON> said. The gold was believed to have been the payroll for workers building the <LOCATION> Sault </LOCATION> Ste. Marie locks in <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Upper </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Peninsula </LOCATION>. When the salvaging work is completed, the wreck could yield a treasure worth about $ 5 million, she said.
