<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> thanked cheering home-state supporters Saturday for their support and received a glowing tribute from Sen. <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>, who said Vice President <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> was a `` dead duck'' in his race for the presidency. `` You have made me what I am, and I am eternally grateful,'' <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> told delegates to the <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> Democratic Convention. `` Nobody has been blessed more than I.'' <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, whose official job at the convention was to introduce <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> to accept the party's endorsement in his re-election bid, opened his remarks by thanking the delegates and state officials `` for making it possible for me and for us to do what we have done the past 15 months.'' `` This commonwealth of ours and its people have set an example that I'm proud of and you're proud of and that I hope will set an example for the nation beginning in January of 1989,'' the <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> governor said. `` We have not only built an economic future for our people that we can be proud of, but we have done it with sensitivity and compassion. And that in the last analysis is the measure of us, and of our state and of our nation.'' For a day, the often-contentious <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> Democrats engaged in a love-fest, paying tribute to <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> and <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>, who is seeking his fifth full term in the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> and whose endorsement was the only major official convention business. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, who noted that he was first elected to the state Legislature the same year <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> began his <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> career _ 1962 _ called the senator `` our leader for many, many years'' and praised <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> for his po