<HEAD>Blaze Destroys Santo Domingo's Largest Shopping Area</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTO DOMINGO, Dominican Republic (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A fire caused by faulty electrical wiring Saturday destroyed most shops and offices in the <LOCATION> Dominican </LOCATION> capital's main commercial center. Several firemen fighting the blaze at <LOCATION> Naca </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Plaza </LOCATION> mall fainted after inhaling the dense smoke, but police reported no other injuries. Most of the mall's more than 50 business offices, shops and boutiques were destroyed by the fire, causing several million dollars in damage, said owners and managers. Officials said the blaze broke out early in the morning when an auxiliary power generator in the <LOCATION> Naco </LOCATION> residential district was turned on, following a power failure in the area. The fire began in the middle of the mall, which only has three entrances leading to large walkways surrounded by shops. Firemen were unable to reach the center of the mall before noon because of the dense smoke. Firemen also had difficulty controlling the blaze due to a lack of water and equipment such as oxygen masks and protective clothing.
