<DATELINE>DOBBS FERRY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 More than 150 anti-abortion demonstrators were arrested on disorderly conduct charges Saturday for blocking the entrance to a women's health center, police said. More than 200 people blocked the doors of the Women's Medical Pavilion around 7:30 a.m., said Sgt. <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Palsy </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Dobbs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ferry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Police </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>. More than 150 were arrested and taken by bus to police headquarters and other municipal buildings, police said. They were released within a few hours on their promise to appear and face trespassing charges. But <PERSON> Juli </PERSON> <PERSON> Loesch </PERSON>, a spokeswoman for Operation Rescue, the Manhattan-based group that staged the demonstration, complained that police kept the demonstrators from leaving to keep them from resuming their protest. `` We believe they are being held in preventive detention in violation of the Constitution,'' <PERSON> Loesch </PERSON> said. It was unclear whether the medical office opened Saturday. In the morning a woman who answered the phone there hung up on a reporter without answering any questions. In the afternoon, an answering service took calls. `` This is a rescue,'' <PERSON> Loesch </PERSON> said. `` We wanted to stop the abortions that were to occur today and to offer alternative solutions to abortion, including counseling and information on medical care.'' Speaking from <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Loesch </PERSON> said police arrested the Rev. <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Lee </PERSON>, pastor of the Neighborhood Church in <LOCATION> Greenwich </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Village </LOCATION>; <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Herliahy </PERSON>, an anti-abortion activist, and <PERSON> Bishop </PERSON> <PERSON> Austin </PERSON> <PERSON> Vaughan </PERSON>, an auxiliary bishop of the archdiocese of <LOCATION> New </LOCATI