<HEAD>Reporters Walk Out Of Rally</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos NY35, NY36</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A newspaper and its reporters were singled out for blame Saturday at a rally for supporters of a black teen-ager who claims she was abducted and raped by white men, and reporters responded by walking out. The rally organizers then banned The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> and several other news organizations from a Sunday morning church service to be attended by the teen. The incident began during a tirade by lawyer <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Vernon </PERSON> <PERSON> Mason </PERSON> about a Newsday story earlier this year that said the Rev. <PERSON> Al </PERSON> <PERSON> Sharpton </PERSON> was a federal informant who wore hidden microphones to meetings with civil rights leaders and organized crime figures. <PERSON> Mason </PERSON>, <PERSON> Sharpton </PERSON> and lawyer <PERSON> Alton </PERSON> <PERSON> Maddox </PERSON> have made a racial issue of the case of <PERSON> Tawana </PERSON> <PERSON> Brawley </PERSON>, 16, of <LOCATION> Wappingers </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Falls </LOCATION>, who claims she was abducted and sexually assaulted by six white men over a four-day period last November. After initially cooperating with authorities, she and her family have refused to participate further, charging a cover-up. <PERSON> Glenda </PERSON> <PERSON> Brawley </PERSON>, the mother of <PERSON> Tawana </PERSON> <PERSON> Brawley </PERSON>, was sentenced to 30 days in jail Monday for failing to appear before a grand jury looking into the case. The lawyers and <PERSON> Sharpton </PERSON> say Mrs. <PERSON> Brawley </PERSON> took `` sanctuary'' at <ORGANIZATION> Bethany </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Baptist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> in the predominantly black <LOCATION> Bedford-Stuyvesant </LOCATION> section of <LOCATION> Brooklyn </LOCATION>, where about 200 people attended the rally. Mrs. <PERSON> Brawley </PERSON> was present but did not speak. At one point, <PERSON> Mason </PERSON> shouted, `` Tell