<BYLINE>By JOE TAYLOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROANOKE, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Maurice </PERSON> <PERSON> Dawkins </PERSON>, a black businessman and former Democrat, won the <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> nomination Saturday to run for the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> seat against former Democratic Gov. <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Robb </PERSON>. <PERSON> Dawkins </PERSON>, 67, is the first black to run for the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> from <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> since Reconstruction. He won a first ballot nomination over two rivals after promising to `` put an end to the era of <PERSON> Chuck </PERSON> <PERSON> Robb </PERSON>'' in a fiery address at the state GOP convention. `` They said it could n't be done, but we did it,'' <PERSON> Dawkins </PERSON> said after his nomination. `` They say <PERSON> Chuck </PERSON> <PERSON> Robb </PERSON> ca n't be beaten, but we're going to beat him.'' <PERSON> Dawkins </PERSON> and <PERSON> Robb </PERSON> will square off for the seat currently held by Rep. <PERSON> Paul </PERSON>. <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Trible </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, who is not seeking re-election. <PERSON> Dawkins </PERSON>, a lobbyist and retired minister who lives in the northern <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> suburbs of <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION>, defeated <PERSON> Andrew </PERSON> <PERSON> Wahlquist </PERSON>, a former <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> aide, and <PERSON> Gil </PERSON> <PERSON> Faulk </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> McLean </LOCATION> attorney, for the nomination. His speech combined a thundering attack on <PERSON> Robb </PERSON> with frequent references to God, faith and family. He ended by leading the delegates in singing `` God <LOCATION> Bless </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>,'' brining the crowd to its feet and swinging many uncommitted delegates into his camp. <PERSON> Dawkins </PERSON> switched to the <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> af