<HEAD>About 60,000 People Participate In Disarmament Rally</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY25</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 About 60,000 people participated Saturday in a march for nuclear disarmament and rally in Central Park that brought together 200 peace, labor, religious and human rights organizations. The event was the city's largest political demonstration since 1982, police said. The activities capped a week of activities in support of the <ORGANIZATION> Third </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> Special Session on Disarmament. The coalition organizing the event is seeking to increase interest in abolishing nuclear weapons by the year 2000. `` This is a <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> event to say, ` We still believe,' `` said <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Yarrow </PERSON> of the folk singing group <PERSON> Peter </PERSON>, <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> and <PERSON> Mary </PERSON>. Along the roads winding through Central Park were booths set up by organizations that distributed literature, sold buttons, T-shirts and records. The day's events began with a torch lighting ceremony at the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION>. The torch came from the Eternal Flame at the <LOCATION> Hiroshima </LOCATION> Memorial in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>. Those who arrived early then marched to Central Park for the international program of cultural presentations and speeches, which featured among others Coretta <PERSON> Scott </PERSON> <PERSON> King </PERSON>, folks singers <PERSON> Ronnie </PERSON> <PERSON> Gilbert </PERSON>, <PERSON> Pete </PERSON> <PERSON> Seeger </PERSON> and <PERSON> Yarrow </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> Midnight </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Oil </ORGANIZATION>, an Australian rock group. <PERSON> Leslie </PERSON> <PERSON> Cagan </PERSON>, national coordinator for the sponsoring coalition, said the demonstrations can have a `` momentous effect on the national political agenda.'' The coalition is calling for the abolition of nuclear weapons, self-determination