<HEAD>LAPD Wins Trial Use of Hollow-Point Bullets; Critics Vow Court
Fight</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Police here have won permission to use hollow-point bullets on a trial basis, outraging critics who say the bullets inflict far more serious wounds than conventional ammunition. `` We're very disturbed,'' said <PERSON> Joel </PERSON> <PERSON> Maliniak </PERSON>, a spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Civil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberties </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> California </ORGANIZATION>. `` These bullets are designed to cause as much bodily harm as possible. They cause greater ripping, tearing and death.'' Hollow-point bullets mushroom to the size of a dime upon impact and have the force of a punch to knock a person down, said police spokesman Cmdr. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Booth </PERSON>. They are far more likely to stop a suspect than round-nose bullets that can pass through someone's body, he said Police Commissioner <PERSON> Bert </PERSON> <PERSON> Boeckmann </PERSON> said statistics show that hollow-points cause no more damage than round-nosed bullets and are less likely to pass through someone's body and ricochet. `` We're getting so many instances of bullets going through people and striking another person,'' <PERSON> Boeckmann </PERSON> said. `` We're all convinced this is an improvement. I see it as something that's safer, by far. The Police Commission approved use of the bullets for a one-year trial period on May 31, said commission President <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Talcott </PERSON>. Public protests blocked an attempt by police Chief <PERSON> Daryl </PERSON> <PERSON> Gates </PERSON> in 1980 to adopt hollow-points, which are used by the <ORGANIZATION> Los </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Angeles </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sheriff </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> and other law