<HEAD>Report: U.S. Growing Coca to Find Ways to Destroy It</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Federal scientists are secretly growing coca as part of an effort to learn how to eradicate the plant from which cocaine is derived, according to a published report. The <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> reported in Sunday's editions that the project has been kept secret because federal officials fear drug dealers or others might threaten the research program or its personnel. Researchers are looking for a reliable chemical or biological means to destroy coca in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> fields, the source of most of the cocaine now reaching the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. The best prospect is a herbicide called tebuthurion, manufactured under the trade name <PERSON> Spike </PERSON> by <ORGANIZATION> Eli </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lilly </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>. Environmentalists have expressed concern that the herbicide could be hazardous to the environment where coca is grown The coca-growing project began about two years ago, according to the Times, which ran photos of plants in a greenhouse near <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. A reporter viewed experiments, including the processing of coca into cocaine. The newspaper agreed not to publish the identity of the researcher who granted access, the site of the research complex or the federal agencies involved. The project included several hundred coca bushes that were raised from seeds `` flown in from <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> in diplomatic pouches,'' the researcher told the Times. Four varieties of the plants are being grown, and researchers have found that herbicides that kill one variety may not work against others. `` Coca is very tough stuff,'' the researcher said, pointing out that a herbicide-treated stalk with brown and withered leaves was growing back.
