<HEAD>Congressional Panels Reviewing Alleged Drinking Incident at
Nuclear Plant</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES HANNAH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Allegations that the manager of a northwestern <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> nuclear power plant was `` disruptive'' in the control room after drinking at a New Year's Eve 1986 party have come under investigation on <LOCATION> Capitol </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hill </LOCATION>, officials say. Officials of <ORGANIZATION> Toledo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Edison </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, the utility that operates the <LOCATION> Davis-Besse </LOCATION> nuclear power plant near <LOCATION> Toledo </LOCATION>, said, however, that their own investigation showed the manager was capable of carrying out his responsibilities despite his drinking. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Scheibel </PERSON>, staff director for the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> investigations subcommittee, said Friday the panel's review of the incident at <ORGANIZATION> Davis-Besse </ORGANIZATION> is in its early stages. `` We're just taking a look at it preliminarily,'' <PERSON> Scheibel </PERSON> said. A congressional source who spoke only on condition of anonymity said the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> investigations subcommittee also has been reviewing the alleged incident for a couple of weeks. In addition, the <ORGANIZATION> Nuclear </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Regulatory </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> is wrapping up its investigation into the allegations, according to <ORGANIZATION> NRC </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Jan </PERSON> <PERSON> Strasma </PERSON>. <PERSON> Strasma </PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION> NRC </ORGANIZATION> initially had accepted the findings of the investigation by <PERSON> Toledo </PERSON> <PERSON> Edison </PERSON>, but started a new review last July after the agency's resident inspector received more information from plant employees. <PERSON> Toledo </PERSON> <PERSON> Edison </PERSON> found that the plant manager had been drinking before arriving at the control room, but concluded: `` It is clear that the individual was in fact fully fit for duty. Accordingly, no disciplinary action is recommended.'' <LOCATION> Davis-Besse </LOCATION>, about 20 miles east of <LOCATION> Toledo </LOCATION>, was shut down for 18 months after a June 9, 1985, incident in which two main and two backup feedwater pumps failed. Operators restarted the pumps and kept the reactor safely covered with cooling water. Since then, the utility has spent about $ 180 million to upgrade the plant. <PERSON> Strasma </PERSON> said the plant was in the process of starting back up the evening of Dec. 31, 1986, when the manager was called to the site to check progress. `` The allegation was that this manager had been drinking and he was disruptive in the control room,'' <PERSON> Strasma </PERSON> said. He said <PERSON> Toledo </PERSON> <PERSON> Edison </PERSON> submitted a report on the incident to the <ORGANIZATION> NRC </ORGANIZATION> on Feb. 19, 1987. The report stated that the manager had been at a New Year's Eve party at which he had consumed alcohol and that when he later went to the control room, he was outspoken and argumentative, <PERSON> Strasma </PERSON> said. The report quoted a person in the control room as characterizing the manager as `` angry and briefly outspoken'' but that the person did not think it surprising or inappropriate. While the utility's report substantiated that the manager was at the plant shortly after drinking alcohol, it said the allegation that his behavior was distracting was subjective and not substantiated. <PERSON> Toledo </PERSON> <PERSON> Edison </PERSON> spokesman <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Kelly </PERSON> said the utility thoroughly investigated the matter and could find nothing to back up the allegation that the manager had been unfit for duty. <PERSON> Strasma </PERSON> said the manager currently retains his position with the utility. The probe was taken over last October by the <ORGANIZATION> NRC </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Investigations </ORGANIZATION>, which reviews possible wrongdoing by licensees, said <PERSON> Strasma </PERSON>, who added that a report on the incident was being written.
