pearance were ambiguous. <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON>, 59, a federal judge since 1968 and chief judge of the southern district of <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> for the past six years, is serving a five-year prison sentence at <ORGANIZATION> Eglin </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Base </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Fla </LOCATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> denied <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON>'s appeal of his perjury conviction last January. He can continue to hold office and draw his salary, however, unless he resigns or is convicted at a <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> impeachment trial. Before <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON> entered prison in March, the Judicial Conference of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, the chief policymaking body of the federal judiciary, reported unanimously to <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> leaders that `` consideration of impeachment may be warranted'' in <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON>'s case. Rep. <PERSON> Don </PERSON> <PERSON> Edwards </PERSON>, D-Calif., chairman of the Judiciary subcommittee that conducted impeachment hearings, said his panel would leave the record open for further comments in <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON>'s case until June 14 Shortly after that date, <PERSON> Edwards </PERSON> said, the panel will decide whether to recommend impeachment by the full House. A separate Judiciary subcommittee headed by Rep. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Conyers </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, D-Mich., ended three weeks of impeachment hearings Thursday on federal judge <PERSON> Alcee </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Hastings </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION>, who was acquitted of bribery conspiracy in 1983 <PERSON> Hastings </PERSON>' fellow judges charged that he actually committed the crime and tried to conceal his involvement by lying under oath and fabricating evidence at 