<HEAD>Soviet Delegation Studies Swedish Welfare State</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHAN RAPP</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A Soviet delegation has spent two weeks in capitalist <LOCATION> Sweden </LOCATION> studying the social welfare system to see whether any aspect could be used to reform the Soviet economic and social system. `` We are not here to copy, we are here to find efficient methods that, within our socialistic system, are the most efficient for our social development,'' Vice Finance Minister <PERSON> Viacheslav </PERSON> <PERSON> Senchagov </PERSON> said Friday as the delegation ended its visit. <LOCATION> Sweden </LOCATION> is a capitalist country, but its taxes are among the world's highest. Tax income finances welfare programs which health, child care and education free for everyone and guarantees liveable retirement pensions. Soviet economic experts and bureacrats examined the Swedish retraining programs, the tax system, the labor exchange and cooperative companies. They also visited factories and farms. Delegates said Soviet leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s `` perestroika'' policy was now in its most active stage It was most important to increase production while safeguarding social goals, they said. Perestroika means restructuring in Russian and is a buzzword for <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s program which seeks to reform the Soviet economy and social system. `` We are looking for a tax system to stimulate innovation and how to use taxes to get work collectives to use the socialist property in the best way,'' <PERSON> Senchagov </PERSON> told a news conference. Speaking through an interpreter, he said the danger of perestroika was that it might create economic inequality. In <LOCATION> Sweden </LOCATION>, incomes are equalized by a progressive taxes that takes as much as 78 percent in the top tax brackets. The delegation arrived to <LOCATION> Sweden </LOCATION> on May 29 at the invitation of social democratic Prime Minister <PERSON> Ingvar </PERSON> <PERSON> Carlsson </PERSON>. It was scheduled to return to <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> today. Another member of the group, <PERSON> Leonid </PERSON> <PERSON> Abalkin </PERSON>, Director of the <ORGANIZATION> Soviet </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Academy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sciences </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ' </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economy </ORGANIZATION>, described the Swedish model as dynamic and efficient. `` The social motives and humanistic goals in <LOCATION> Sweden </LOCATION> ... are very attractive to us, and we sympathize with the system,'' he said. Asked why the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> had started turning to capitalistic countries for ideas <PERSON> Abalkin </PERSON> said `` there is nothing peculiar about the fact that we after 70 years turn to other countries.'' `` The Socialistic system is open for all positive things in the world,'' he said. Head of delegation, <PERSON> Anatoliy </PERSON> <PERSON> Miliukov </PERSON>, said <LOCATION> Sweden </LOCATION>'s extensive labor exchange and retraining programs, which include government subsidies to companies that give workers time off for study, were of great interest. He said that as a result of perestroika the number of officials at various ministries are being cut down sharply and that in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> alone the number of employed in half of the ministries had been cut by 30-40 percent. `` We have retired a lot of these people, others have been transferred to other institutions, for instance to research,'' <PERSON> Miliukov </PERSON> said.
