<SECOND>PM-Hungary,0565</SECOND>
<HEAD>Institute Warns Radical Measures Needed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> needs radical reforms and faces years of social upheaval before its economic and social crisis will end, a private Hungarian think tank said. In a separate discussion on state television, a top Communist party official revealed that <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION>'s economic woes meant that its defense commitments to the <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> Pact were not increased this year, and will not grow in real terms through 1990. In a report Friday, the state news agency, <ORGANIZATION> MTI </ORGANIZATION>, summarized what it said were the results of a report by the <ORGANIZATION> Financial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, a former state institute that went private last year after Communist authorities threatened to close it for its critical analyses. The new analysis, entitled `` Reports From the Tunnel,'' said <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> `` now faces a criticial situation externally and internally'' because reforms begun in the late 1960s did not go far enough in dismantling centralized state control over the economy. `` Production is growing ever more slowly, the situation of small business has become less stable, the inflationary pressure remains, the ` self-restraint' by companies about price increases will not last long and the efforts to curb budgetary spending have not been successful,'' said <PERSON> Istvan </PERSON> <PERSON> Csillag </PERSON>, deputy head of the research company. Inflation has already touched 18 percent in <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> this year, and many experts expect it to go higher. <ORGANIZATION> MTI </ORGANIZATION> quoted <PERSON> Csillag </PERSON> as saying that the currently favorable assessment of <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION>'s prospects abroad will soon change unless more reform is adopted. With a gross hard currency debt of $ 18 billion, <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> is highly dependent on Western assessments of its performance and reforms to gain further credits from governments, banks and the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Monetary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fund </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> MTI </ORGANIZATION> quoted the <ORGANIZATION> Financial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> as saying significant changes were needed, including a shift to satisfying overall market demand rather than selected markets and new forms of ownership. If such changes were implemented, the report said, `` then we may be out of the present critical situation in five to eight years' time. But it noted that this would only occur `` at a price of the upheavals that structural change will entail.'' <ORGANIZATION> MTI </ORGANIZATION> quoted the firm's manager, <PERSON> Marton </PERSON> <PERSON> Tardos </PERSON>, as saying it was necessary to create popular support for changes even if they entailed unemployment and other unpopular reductions in the social support mechanism. Until the mid-1980s, unemployment was unknown in <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION>, which like other Soviet bloc nations touted full employment as one of the achievements of Communism. <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> and other east European nations have now admitted that people employed in unprofitable state enterprises will have to face at least temporary job loss as state subsidies are shifted from the loss-making firms to more profitable enterprises. One area of Communist budgets that so far has seemed immune from cuts has been defense. But Politburo member <PERSON> Miklos </PERSON> <PERSON> Nemeth </PERSON> indicated on Hungarian television Thursday night that <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION>'s economic woes have also affected military spending. He said 1987 defense spending, including costs for <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> militia and for clothing and housing soldiers totaled about $ 1 billion. The real value of defense spending was not increased in 1988, <PERSON> Nemeth </PERSON> said, declining to give figures. <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> Pact commitments also were not increased as in the past, but kept the same in real terms, <PERSON> Nemeth </PERSON> said. Again, he provided no figures.
