<HEAD>Use of Herbicide Halted Except In Limited Instances In Northwest</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> says the last two manufacturers of a weedkiller that can cause birth defects must stop selling the herbicide, but the agency will allow short-term continued use on some food products in three Northwestern states. <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> Administrator <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> on Friday announced the agency has reached a settlement with the two makers of the herbicide dinoseb that would halt most current sales and distribution of the product. But the government has said <ORGANIZATION> Cedar </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chemical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chemical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, both near <LOCATION> Memphis </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Tenn. </LOCATION>, can sell their existing stock for use during the rest of this year on dry peas, lentils, chickpeas and green peas in the states of <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION>. The remaining stock may be used in 1988 and 1989 on berries in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Al </PERSON> <PERSON> Heier </PERSON> said <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> decided to allow limited continued use of dinoseb into 1989 although it can cause birth defects and poses a hazard to men's ability to have children. <PERSON> Heier </PERSON> said there is no substitute herbicide to treat weeds affecting certain plants in the Northwest. Certain crops `` would have been rather devastated'' if the <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> had banned the weedkiller altogether, said <PERSON> Heier </PERSON>. <PERSON> Heier </PERSON> characterized the exceptions as small and said the tight restrictions were designed to protect people from exposure to the chemical. Several environmental groups had opposed any further sales of the weedkiller and any provision allowing for the use of existing supplies. But <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> estimated it would cost $ 40 million to purchase all existing supplies of dinoseb from chemical companies and another $ 155 million to dispose of it as federal law requires. Friday's agreement came as a result of a challenger by Cedar and <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> to an <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> emergency ban of dinoseb issued in October 1986.
