<HEAD>OPEC Ministers Split Over Cutting Oil Production</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEDE prospects uncertain.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By COTTEN TIMBERLAKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Disagreements among <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> ministers meeting here today could cut as much a $ 2 off the price of a barrel of oil, benefiting consumers the world over, analysts say. One faction of the oil-producing group is pushing for a cut in production. A Western-oriented camp is bracing to block the move. <LOCATION> Venezuela </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Libya </LOCATION>, and <LOCATION> Algeria </LOCATION> want a production cut to keep oil prices at $ 18 a barrel. But a Saudi Arabia-led group has opposed the idea, which failed to gain the support of oil ministers at this week's Arab Summit in <LOCATION> Algiers </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Algeria </LOCATION>. Twelve of the 28-year-old cartel's members agreed in December to extend a quota of 15 million barrels a day until June 30. <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>, which is at war with <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>, refused to sign the accord because it demanded a production quota equal to <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION>'s. Now, the members of the <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Petroleum </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exporting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Countries </ORGANIZATION> are so divided over production controls that many analysts expect them to fight over the issue for at least a week _ and then give up. They were expected simply to extend the existing quota until the end of the year. <PERSON> Harry </PERSON> <PERSON> Neustein </PERSON>, a New York-based oil trader who was to observe the meeting, says the disagreement will cause oil prices to fall. `` It's going south, which of course, is great for the consumer,'' <PERSON> Neustein </PERSON> said. Some analysts said the lack of a new accord could force prices down by as much as $ 2 a barrel below the organization's target of $ 18. The oil markets also showed little confidence in the ministers' ability to reach a consensus The July contract price of <ORGANIZATION> West </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Intermediate </ORGANIZATION>, the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> benchmark crude oil, fell 34 cents to $ 16.73 a barrel on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> on Friday. That was its lowest level in more than two months. In addition, the cartel nations are doing little to help boost the price. Currently, they are producing an estimated 18.5 million barrels a day, 3.4 million barrels a day more than their agreement allows. The majority camp, led by <LOCATION> Venezuela </LOCATION>, wants to cut production to push oil prices up nearer <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION>'s target price. <LOCATION> Venezuela </LOCATION> ideally would like to cut production jointly with the interested producers outside the cartel. The non-OPEC members involved in the dialogue with <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> are <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Oman </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Malaysia </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Norway </LOCATION> is attending the meeting as observer, while <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> is not represented. <LOCATION> Venezuela </LOCATION> aggressively backed an unsuccessful attempt by non-OPEC producers in late April to get the cartel to agree to cut production. A minority of four <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> nations, led by heavyweight <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION> _ <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION>'s largest producer _ blocked that attempt at the extraordinary <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> meeting six weeks ago at which no new agreement was reached. At the mid-year meeting, the minority opponents of the plan, again led by <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION>, want to boost production to match predictions of an increase in demand in the last six months of 1988, analysts said. However, the cartel's members do n't even agree on how large demand will be. Estimates range from 17.6 million barrels a day to 18.9 million barrels a day. In the first half of the year, demand was 17.7 million barrels a day, analysts say.
