<HEAD>Fast-Attack Submarine Contracts Awarded</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CALLAHAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> awarded a contract for two of this year's fast-attack submarines to a <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> company and indicated <ORGANIZATION> Connecticut-based </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electric </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Boat </ORGANIZATION> can win the third sub only if it lowers its price. The <ORGANIZATION> Newport </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Shipbuilding </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Drydock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> won a $ 612 million contract on Friday to build two SSN-688 Los Angeles-class submarines, scheduled to be completed in August 1993. <ORGANIZATION> Newport </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> outbid Electric Boat, a division of <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dynamics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, said <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> Lt. <PERSON> Brian </PERSON> <PERSON> Cullin </PERSON>. The <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> said it would negotiate with Electric Boat to get a lower price on the third submarine, <PERSON> Cullin </PERSON> said. The announcement is a disappointment for <ORGANIZATION> Electric </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Boat </ORGANIZATION>, which lost out on last year's fast-attack sub competition 4-0 to its Virginia-based arch rival. Both companies rely heavily on the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> contracts. <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> officials told Rep. <PERSON> Sam </PERSON> <PERSON> Gejdenson </PERSON>, D-Conn., that <ORGANIZATION> Electric </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Boat </ORGANIZATION> raised its bid at the final stage of the contract competition, a time when companies usually lower their offers, said <PERSON> Gejdenson </PERSON> aide Chip Partner It was not known why Electric Boat hiked its price. Electric Boat spokesman <PERSON> Neil </PERSON> <PERSON> Ruenzel </PERSON> declined comment. In a prepared statement, the company said the loss illustrates that price `` is the acknowledged driver in today's defense industry environment,'' and that <ORGANIZATION> Electric </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Boat </ORGANIZATION> will have to lower labor costs to compete with <ORGANIZATION> Newport </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION>. Electric Boat is in negotiations with unionized workers for a new contract. The current contract expires June 30. `` The major cost in our submarine construction is labor. <ORGANIZATION> Newport </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION>, our competitor, has lower labor costs. Today's announcement is a clear mandate for <ORGANIZATION> Electric </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Boat </ORGANIZATION> to hold labor costs in line and to re-examine all possible options to lowering other key costs elements,'' said <ORGANIZATION> Electric </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Boat </ORGANIZATION> in a prepared statement issued Friday. <PERSON> Ruenzel </PERSON> said it was `` too early'' to assess the potential impact on employment. Union officials could not be reached late Friday for comment. The SSN-688 submarine, a 6,900-ton vessel as long as a professional football field, is designed to hunt down enemy surface ships and subs. They are armed with <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> 48 anti-submarine torpedoes, Harpoon missiles and Tomahawk cruise missiles. The two sub builders have been competing for the fast-attack sub contracts since the first award in 1970. Electric Boat has won 31 SSN-688 contracts. Friday's awards brings <ORGANIZATION> Newport </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION>' total up to 27. Last year, <ORGANIZATION> Newport </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> won all four fast-attack submarines awarded by the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION>. In 1986, <ORGANIZATION> Electric </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Boat </ORGANIZATION> won all four contracts. The sub contracts are enormously important to the shipyards. Electric Boat is the region's largest private employer, with 18,000 workers at its main plant in <LOCATION> Groton </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Conn. </LOCATION>, and 6,000 at its yard in <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kingstown </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> R.I. </LOCATION> <ORGANIZATION> Newport </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> has more than 26,000 workers at the <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> shipyard. In <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Newport </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Schnaedter </PERSON> said: `` A contract of this size adds a certain degree of long-range stability to our work force, and it's good news for the yard to get two of them.''
