<FIRST>a a PM-AnotherLook:FarmCredit Adv13   06-11 1181</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Another Look: Farm Credit, Adv 13,1210</SECOND>
<NOTE>$Adv13</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Mon PMs, June 13, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Results of Farm Credit Legislation Still Not Clear</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARGARET BAUMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OTIS, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Agricultural Credit Act of 1987 initially appeared to be a lifeline for ranchers and farmers drowning in debt to federal loan programs. Yet five months after President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> signed the bill and federal officials hailed it as a critical step toward helping rural landowners hold onto their acres, `` the jury is still out'' for thousands of borrowers on billions of dollars in delinquent loans. In the first quarter of this year, the act helped 8,500 `` distressed'' loans to be restructured so farmers and ranchers could keep their properties, according to <PERSON> Ruth </PERSON> <PERSON> Ross </PERSON>, spokeswoman for the <ORGANIZATION> Farm </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Credit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corporation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION>. But many other farmers owe their money to the <ORGANIZATION> Farmers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Home </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>, whose regulations under the act are not yet settled, and some have been unable to apply for the aid provided by the landmark legislation. The borrower-owned Farm Credit System of banks and lending cooperatives lost $ 4.8 billion from 1985 through last year, said <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Brent </PERSON> <PERSON> Beesley </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> Farm </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Credit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corporation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION>, which oversees the Farm Credit System. The system's problems, coupled with land devaluation and low crop prices, were forcing thousands of farms onto the auction block, <PERSON> Beesley </PERSON> said. The act provides up to $ 4 billion in federal funds to financially troubled farm credit institutions through 1992, protecting farmers' stock in those banks and cooperatives. It also requires farm loans to be restructured _ changing the terms in some way so the debt can still be repaid _ if that would cost less than foreclosure. Until the legislation passed, loan restructuring was a voluntary effort, said <PERSON> Jeff </PERSON> <PERSON> Oates </PERSON>, a spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> Farm </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Credit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corporation </ORGANIZATION>. `` Now the law says, ` You will restructure.''' `` I think it's working just fine,'' <PERSON> Beesley </PERSON> said of the legislation. `` Investors have greater confidence in the system, and so do borrowers. We're very pleased with the act.'' But at the office of the Coalition to Save Rural <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>, based in this plains town in northeastern <LOCATION> Colorado </LOCATION>, the hotline rings steadily. `` It's sort of a big question mark,'' said <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Glover </PERSON>, who estimated he had fielded hundreds of calls about the act. `` Because of the complexities in borrowing practices, what happens in one lending institution could affect them in another federal institution.'' The major stumbling block in the process arises from the structure of the federal lending agencies and the pattern of how farmers borrow. Many farmers have multiple loans spread among the various lenders. The 37 Farm Land Banks, for example, make long-term land loans, and the 387 lending cooperatives known as Production Credit Associations make short-term operating loans. Those agencies come under the Farm Credit System. But the <ORGANIZATION> Farmers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Home </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>, which makes both types of loans, is supervised by the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION>, and rules for the <ORGANIZATION> FmHA </ORGANIZATION> are still in the public approval process. The FmHA has balked at going along with restructuring plans for borrowers that hold its loans as well as others, fearing vulnerability. `` I had a case over in the <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Slope </LOCATION> where the lender at the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Land </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> said they would work anything out with the farmer, as long as the <ORGANIZATION> FmHA </ORGANIZATION> would agree to it,'' <PERSON> Glover </PERSON> said. `` FmHA could n't agree to anything because the rules and regulations were n't out yet _ and they do n't know what they can agree to.'' <PERSON> Jerry </PERSON> <PERSON> Slaugh </PERSON>, a consultant who helps farmers with restructuring, predicted it might take until January for the <ORGANIZATION> FmHA </ORGANIZATION> to be absorbed into the act. `` Until then, anyone with a <ORGANIZATION> Farmers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Home </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> loan is just in limbo,'' he said. `` It's just putting a litte bit of a shadow on our efforts out there because they -LRB- FmHA -RRB- are not ready to sit down at the table and negotiate about restructuring.'' So far this year, <PERSON> Slaugh </PERSON> says he has saved 10 farms by restructuring loans. He is working on about 50 more with <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Byers </PERSON>, a former farmer and his partner in Ag Management Consultants, based in Grand Junction. The company has a contract with the state's rural job training program to help indebted farmers. It also has clients with loans from <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Land </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Banks </ORGANIZATION> in the <LOCATION> Wichita </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Kan. </LOCATION>, district. Slaugh estimated that those banks hold about 40,000 loans in <LOCATION> Colorado </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Oklahoma </LOCATION>, and that 4,000 of them are distressed, meaning they are delinquent or potentially deliquent. That's about half as many as a few years ago. `` The new legislation has given us more tools,'' he said. `` At this point, the jury is still out. We've had some success _ not as much as we'd like to see. -LRB- But -RRB- compared to when we started three years ago, it's a world of difference.'' <PERSON> Terry </PERSON> <PERSON> Gutschenritter </PERSON>, vice president of special credit for the Farm Credit System in <LOCATION> Wichita </LOCATION>, said his agency last year opened a special credit department for distressed loans and was able to `` bring back'' about 45 percent of 5,000 loans so families could stay on their farms, he said. For farmers and ranchers with distressed loans, the crucial step is to respond quickly to notices from lenders, warned <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Stencel </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> Rocky </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mountain </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Farmers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION>, a grass-roots general farm organization with 18,000 members in <LOCATION> Colorado </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Wyoming </LOCATION>. `` Borrowers are currently receiving letters from the Farm Credit System advising them of their rights to ask for their loans to be restructured,'' <PERSON> Stencel </PERSON> said. `` If borrowers do n't respond within 45 days, Farm Credit can begin foreclosure. `` If farmers miss the deadline, they still have the right to request restructuring, but the cost of foreclosure may diminish chances of restructuring as -LRB- the less expensive -RRB- alternative.'' Agriculture attorneys <PERSON> Judith </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shively </PERSON> and <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Dworkin </PERSON>, partners with offices near the state Capitol in <LOCATION> Denver </LOCATION>, see the 1987 legislation as a tool _ particularly because it obligates the lender to notify the borrower before any foreclosure action is taken. `` We have found ... farmers as a group have always been hard-working, God-fearing people who have paid their debts, and now they find they ca n't pay their debts,'' <PERSON> Dworkin </PERSON> said. `` And when you have to ask that type of an individual to file bankruptcy, you get tremendous resistance. But farmers today `` have to be aware of every single government program and use it to the max,'' he said. They also must know what it takes to grow cattle or crops _ and be good money managers, too, he said. Many farmers in trouble today meet those criteria, but bad weather and the economy bring them to the Rural Coalition, consultants like <PERSON> Slaugh </PERSON> and attorneys who are experts in agricultural law. `` The legislation will be beneficial, but it wo n't eliminate the farm crisis,'' <PERSON> Gutschenritter </PERSON> said. `` A positive income situation _ better prices _ is what is needed. `` I think it's going to be a much wiser farm credit system as a result of these times. It will make us tougher, better farmers.''
</TEXT>
