<HEAD>Market Awaits New Junk Bond Issues</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARIANN CAPRINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Traders and investors alike are scrounging for new junk in the credit markets. They are eagerly awaiting the high-yield, high-risk junk bonds that will be issued to help finance many of the mergers and acquisitions that have taken place recently on the corporate takeover trail. `` There have been a number of deals completed in the last two months where it is anticipated that -LRB- junk bond -RRB- financing will be accomplished,'' said <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dahood </PERSON>, a high-yield bond analyst at <ORGANIZATION> Smith </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Barney </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> , </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Harris </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Upham </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Co. He said British industrialist <PERSON> Brian </PERSON> <PERSON> Beazer </PERSON> is likely to use junk bonds to finance at least some of his $ 1.7 billion buyout of the Pittsburgh-based cement company, <ORGANIZATION> Koppers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> `` And <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Standard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> is almost certain to come to market at some point,'' he added, referring to the $ 2.5 billion leveraged buyout of the company that is being led by <ORGANIZATION> Kelso </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Co. It also is anticipated that <LOCATION> Toronto </LOCATION> retailer <ORGANIZATION> Robert </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Campeau </ORGANIZATION> will raise more than $ 1 billion through the sale of junk bonds to facilitate his acquisition of <ORGANIZATION> Federated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stores </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Campeau </ORGANIZATION> also is likely to rely on junk bonds to finance the spinoff of <PERSON> Ralph </PERSON>'s supermarket chain as a subsidiary `` Some of the takeovers do create very large issues, and that alone is a sudden injection of product into the market,'' said <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Waill </PERSON>, a managing director at <ORGANIZATION> L.F. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rothschild </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Unterberg </PERSON>, <PERSON> Towbin </PERSON>. `` In terms of getting business going, I suppose it's good _ it does create a certain amount of motion,'' he said. A slowdown in mergers and acquisitions since the market crash resulted in a reduced supply of new junk bond issues. `` That may be contributing to the richness of the market,'' <PERSON> Dahood </PERSON> said referring to the high prices at which are selling and trading. Conversely, yields on many of these debt issues are not as handsome as they have been historically. <PERSON> Dahood </PERSON> characterized current returns as `` rather skimpy.'' When comparing relative yields, `` the junk bond market is providing a rather skimpy incremental return to the <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> market at the 10-year issuance,'' he said. Because high-yield debt securities often are issued for 10-year terms, they typically are measured against the 10-year Treasury bill. Junk bonds currently are trading about 425 to 475 basis points above the 10-year <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> bill, which is hovering just under 9 percent. A basis point is one-hundredth of a percentage point. In the past, however, junk bonds have traded as much as 600 basis points above the government security, and, more recently, 500 to 550 basis points above, <PERSON> Dahood </PERSON> said. Putting it another way, `` the premium for accepting the risk today is somewhat smaller than it has been,'' he noted. In addition to the takeover issues that might revive the market, some analysts say corporations are being driven to lock in fixed-rate debt as overall interest rates move higher. `` Companies that launched leveraged buyouts late last year and financed them with bank and bridge loans at floating rates are now getting nervous as interest rates move up,'' noted <PERSON> Gail </PERSON> <PERSON> Hessol </PERSON>, managing director of industrial rating at <ORGANIZATION> Standard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Poor </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>. One attractive option is to sell fixed-rate public debt Despite the high level of risk associated with junk bonds and allegations of scandal and wrongdoing at <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Burnham </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lambert </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, the pioneer in junk-bond underwriting, investor interest remains keen. Some estimate there are some $ 160 billion in outstanding junk bonds, with as much as 10 percent held by individuals as opposed to institutional investors. A surge in junk-bond mutual funds is also making the high-yield instrument more accessible to the average investor. Quoting from a recent government study, <PERSON> Dahood </PERSON> said there were 23 junk bond mutual funds in 1981 with assets of $ 3.1 billion; by Sept. 30, 1987, the number had mushroomed to 72, and their assets totaled more than $ 30 billion.
</TEXT>
