<HEAD>Central Bankers, Others Paint Picture Of Economic Stability</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VIVIAN MARINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A gathering of top-level executives from the world's biggest banks produced a picture of economic harmony, supported by improved trade, stable exchange rates and healthy growth. While few economists would dispute those assertions, made this past week at the 34th annual <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Monetary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conference </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>, many agreed the current state of affairs, particularly involving currencies, was more a product of inertia than policymaking. `` Policy is on hold,'' said <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Brusca </PERSON>, chief economist for <ORGANIZATION> Nikko </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>. International in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> `` The policymakers are kind of hemmed in. They do n't know what to do.'' <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Greenspan </PERSON> made it clear during the three-day <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> meeting that he did n't want the dollar to fall any further, for fear it could harm ongoing attempts to reduce the huge <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trade deficit. <PERSON> Greenspan </PERSON> told a separate press briefing the `` adjustment process,'' by which the dollar has been allowed to depreciate over the past three years to enhance the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trade picture by making exports less expensive abroad, `` has made significant progress.'' But he said since manufacturers already are running at or near capacity levels due to healthy export growth, further dollar declines would n't help them sell more goods overseas or anywhere else, facilitating inflationary pressures. <ORGANIZATION> Bundesbank </ORGANIZATION> President <PERSON> Karl </PERSON> <PERSON> Otto </PERSON> <PERSON> Poehl </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> France </ORGANIZATION> Governor <PERSON> Jacques </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Larosiere </PERSON> publicly agreed with <PERSON> Greenspan </PERSON>. <PERSON> Poehl </PERSON> also made assurances that his country was n't trying to drive down the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> currency, discounting recent dollar sales as a routine effort to trim dollar reserves. Other central bankers at the conference included: Bank of <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> Governor <PERSON> Robin </PERSON> <PERSON> Leigh-Pemberton </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mexico </ORGANIZATION> Director General <PERSON> Miguel </PERSON> <PERSON> Mancera </PERSON> and <PERSON> Takeshi </PERSON> <PERSON> Ohta </PERSON>, deputy governor for international relations for the <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Japan </ORGANIZATION>. Some currency traders and economists remained skeptical about the underlying motives of <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> and about how long the major industrialized nations could maintain stability. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Resler </PERSON>, chief economist for <ORGANIZATION> Nomura </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, said, `` There seems to be an emerging technical reason for the dollar to be on the firm side in the next month or so,'' partly due to <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> agricultural sales to the Soviets and Chinese. He said the <ORGANIZATION> Bundesbank </ORGANIZATION> might privately be `` trying to temper the upward pressure of the dollar that might emerge. A rise in the dollar, should it occur, would bring instability in the markets because it's not sustainable.'' Economists say the upbeat picture publicly presented by the central bankers this past week amounted to an `` open-mouth policy'' clearly aimed at maintaining the narrow trading range for currencies that has existed in recent months. `` There's PR and hot air involved here ... They want to enhance the view that they are unified in the open. They prefer the status,'' said <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Ward </PERSON> <PERSON> McCarthy </PERSON>, chief financial economist for <ORGANIZATION> Merrill </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lynch </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Capital </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Markets </ORGANIZATION>. But there are drawbacks to resisting change, economists say. For one thing, `` there's no lure to foreign capital to make currency gains on their dollar holdings,'' said <PERSON> Brusca </PERSON>. `` As long as they hold the dollar in this narrow trading range you have monetary policy effectively transmitted as though it were a fixed-rate system,'' said <PERSON> Brusca </PERSON>. `` And even though the rates in this sytem are ` fixed' they're not really fixed and you ca n't be sure the floor under the dollar is solid and dependable.'' The currency markets have been trading on a `` floating rate'' system since early 1973, following about three decades of fixed rates that grew out of the historic post-World War II <LOCATION> Bretton </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Woods </LOCATION> agreement. The stage was set for a drop in the dollar in September 1985, when the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and its four major trading partners agreed to devalue the currency to help reduce the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trade shortfall and stave off protectionist legislation. Last year, however, that same group agreed that further decines in the dollar's value would be `` counterproductive.'' In the last three years, the dollar has lost half its value against such currencies as the West German mark and Japanese yen. It has fallen less against the currencies of such major trading partners as <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION>.
</TEXT>
