<HEAD>Glut Of Frozen Pork Bellies Is Good News For BLT Lovers</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Will be followed later in cycle with an ADD containing weekly
price trends</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Lovers of bacon-lettuce-and-tomato sandwiches may be inclined to add an extra layer of bacon to their BLTs this summer. A glut of frozen pork bellies forced futures prices into a virtual free fall this past week and analysts say retail prices for bacon, which is made from pork bellies, will likely plummet as well. The futures market for frozen pork bellies was created to ensure adequate supplies of bellies during the summer, when demand for bacon peaks and supplies of slaughter-ready hogs traditionally bottoms out. Dealers typically stockpile pork bellies in freezers during the fall and winter, then thaw them out and slice them into bacon during the late spring and summer. Last year, light hog production resulted in tight supplies of frozen pork bellies for the summer months and futures prices soared last summer above 90 cents a pound, a five-year high. Dealers compensated by packing away lots of pork bellies during last fall and winter. They put so many bellies in cold storage that supplies swelled to nearly 103 million pounds by May 1, more than double the previous year's May 1 figure and the third largest total on record for that date, according to the <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>. `` This year they got carried away when they put bellies into storage,'' said <PERSON> Chuck </PERSON> <PERSON> Levitt </PERSON>, an analyst in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> with <ORGANIZATION> Shearson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lehman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hutton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> `` They went from a period of deficit to one of tremendous surplus in one year because they overcompensated for having run out last summer,'' he said. Because of this abundance, the price on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> for July delivery of frozen pork bellies has plunged 11 percent already this month, from 56.32 cents a pound on May 31 to 50.07 cents on Friday. Analysts said they expected the decline to continue until prices fall low enough to stimulate demand _ possibly as low as 40 cents a pound. And those prices are certain to filter down to the retail level, analysts said. `` They should be able to offer relatively attractive bacon prices this summer,'' said <PERSON> Dale </PERSON> <PERSON> Durccholz </PERSON>, an analyst with <ORGANIZATION> AgriVisor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Bloomington </LOCATION>, Ill. In addition to the large supplies of frozen pork bellies, the market faces good supplies of higher-quality fresh bellies caused by an unseasonably high number of hog slaughters, analysts said. Packers have not cut down on kills because low cash prices for pork products have narrowed their profit margins, said <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Hare </PERSON>, an analyst with <ORGANIZATION> Smith </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Barney </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> , </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Harris </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Upham </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. And <PERSON> Durccholz </PERSON> said some hog producers, faced with rising feed costs due to the spring drought, may be partially liquidating their herds, thus adding to the number of animals available for slaughter. <PERSON> O'Hare </PERSON> said frozen pork belly futures prices may rebound briefly before sliding lower. `` Technically, the bellies have definitely got to be oversold at this point,'' he said. `` It's low enough that at some point soon, you've got to get people saying ` Hey, this is overdone,' and going in and buying it.''
</TEXT>
